# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: propfan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an effort that was led by Faisal of Saudi Arabia, the initial countries that OAPEC targeted were Canada, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This list was later expanded to include Portugal, Rhodesia, and South Africa.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In March 1974, OAPEC lifted the embargo, but the price of oil had risen by nearly 300%: from US$3 per barrel ($19/m3) to nearly US$12 per barrel ($75/m3) globally.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Prices in the United States were significantly higher than the global average.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After it was implemented, the embargo caused an oil crisis, or "shock", with many short- and long-term effects on the global economy as well as on global politics.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The 1973 embargo later came to be referred to as the **first oil shock**.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A second oil shock occurred in 1979 in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, there has been conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, including several wars.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked by Israel's southern port of Eilat being blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to French and British investors.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As a result of the war, the Suez Canal was closed for several months between 1956 and 1957.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt closing the Suez Canal for eight years.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Yom Kippur War, the canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel's war effort.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1969, American domestic production of oil was peaking and could not keep pace with increasing demand from vehicles.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The US was importing 350 million barrels (56 million cubic metres) per year by the late 1950s, mostly from Venezuela and Canada.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because of transportation costs and tariffs, it never purchased much oil from the Middle East.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, US production had declined to 16% of global output.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Eisenhower imposed quotas on foreign oil that would stay in place between 1959 and 1973.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Critics called it the "drain America first" policy.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Some scholars believe the policy contributed to the decline of domestic US oil production in the early 1970s.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The cheapness of oil compared with coal led to the decline of the coal industry.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1951, 51% of the United States' energy came from coal, and by 1973, only 19% of American industry was coal-based.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The decline in domestic oil production, combined with the country's increasing reliance on oil as a source of power, made the US economy vulnerable to a foreign oil embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When Richard Nixon became US president in 1969, he assigned George Shultz to head a committee to review the Eisenhower-era quota program.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Shultz's committee recommended that the quotas be abolished and replaced with tariffs, but Nixon decided to keep the quotas due to vigorous political opposition.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon imposed a price ceiling on oil in August 1971 as demand for oil was increasing and production was declining, which increased dependence on oil imports as consumption was bolstered by low prices.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, Nixon announced the end of the quota system.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Between 1970 and 1973 US imports of crude oil had nearly doubled, reaching 6.2 million barrels per day in 1973.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until 1973, an abundance of oil supply had kept the market price of oil lower than the posted price.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, American oil production peaked and the United States began to import more oil.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Oil imports rose by 52% between 1969 and 1972.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1972, 83% of the American oil imports came from the Middle East.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the price for a barrel of oil remained at $1.80, meaning that with the effects of inflation considered the price of oil in real terms got progressively lower throughout the decade, with Americans paying less for oil in 1969 than they had in 1959.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Even after a price for a barrel of oil rose to $2.00 in 1971, adjusted for inflation, people in the Western nations were paying less for oil in 1971 than they had in 1958.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The extremely low price of oil served as the basis for the "long summer" of prosperity and mass affluence that began in 1945.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), was founded by five oil producing countries at a Baghdad conference on 14 September 1960.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The five founding members of OPEC were Venezuela, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Kuwait.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was organized after the oil companies slashed the posted price of oil, but the posted price of oil remained consistently higher than the market price of oil between 1961 and 1972.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1963, the Seven Sisters controlled 86% of the oil produced by OPEC countries, but by 1970 the rise of "independent oil companies" had decreased their share to 77%.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The entry of three new oil producers—Algeria, Libya and Nigeria—meant that by 1970, 81 oil companies were doing business in the Middle East.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the early 1960s Libya, Indonesia and Qatar joined OPEC.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was generally regarded as ineffective until political turbulence in Libya and Iraq strengthened their position in 1970.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Additionally, increasing Soviet influence provided oil producing countries with alternative means of transporting oil to markets.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under the Tehran Price Agreement of 1971, signed on 14 February, the posted price of oil was increased and, due to a decline in the value of the US dollar relative to gold, certain anti-inflationary measures were enacted.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A severe drain on US gold reserves lead to higher inflation and lack of confidence in the strength of the dollar, President Nixon issued Executive Order 11615 on August 15, 1971, which closed the gold window.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This action made the dollar inconvertible to gold directly, except on the open market, and was soon dubbed the *Nixon Shock*, leading eventually to the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1976.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because oil was priced in dollars, oil producers' real income decreased when the dollar started to float free of the old link to gold.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1971, OPEC issued a joint communiqué stating that from then on, they would price oil in terms of a fixed amount of gold.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After 1971, OPEC was slow to readjust prices to reflect this depreciation.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] From 1947 to 1967, the dollar price of oil had risen by less than two percent per year.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until the oil shock, the price had also remained fairly stable versus other currencies and commodities.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC ministers had not developed institutional mechanisms to update prices in sync with changing market conditions, so their real incomes lagged.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The substantial price increases of 1973–1974 largely returned their prices and corresponding incomes to former levels in terms of commodities such as gold.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab oil producing countries had attempted to use oil as leverage to influence political events on two prior occasions—the first was the Suez Crisis in 1956 when the United Kingdom, France and Israel invaded Egypt.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During the conflict the Syrians sabotaged both the Trans-Arabian Pipeline and the Iraq–Baniyas pipeline, which disrupted the supply of oil to Western Europe.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The second instance was when war broke out between Egypt and Israel in 1967, but despite continued Egyptian and Syrian enmity against Israel, the embargo lasted only a few months.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most scholars agree that the 1967 embargo was ineffective.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Although some members of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) supported the use of oil as a weapon to influence the political outcome of the Arab–Israeli conflict, Saudi Arabia had traditionally been the strongest supporter of separating oil from politics.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudis were wary of the tactic due to the availability of oil from non-Arab oil producing countries, and in the decades leading up to the crisis, the region's conservative monarchies had grown dependent on Western support to ensure their continued survival as Nasserism gained traction.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the other hand, Algeria, Iraq and Libya had strongly supported the use of oil as a weapon in the conflict.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab newspapers like the Egyptian *Al-Ahram*, Lebanese *An-Nahar* and Iraqi *Al-Thawra* had historically been supportive of the use of oil as a weapon.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, President Nasser of Egypt died and was succeeded by Anwar Sadat, a man who believed in the diplomacy of surprise, in engaging in sudden moves to upset the diplomatic equilibrium.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat liked to say that his favourite game was backgammon, a game where skill and persistence was rewarded, but was best won by sudden gambles, making an analogy between how he played backgammon and conducted his diplomacy.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under Nasser, Egypt and Saudi Arabia had engaged what was known as the Arab Cold War, but Sadat got along very well with King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, forming an alliance between the most populous Arab state and the wealthiest Arab state.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Unlike the secularist Nasser, Sadat was a pious Muslim and he had a strong personal rapport with King Faisal, who was an equally pious Muslim.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The man largely in charge of American foreign policy, the National Security Adviser, Henry Kissinger, later admitted that he was so engrossed with the Paris peace talks to end the Vietnam war that he and others in Washington missed the significance of the Egyptian-Saudi alliance.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time that Sadat moved closer to Saudi Arabia, he also wanted a rapprochement with the United States and to move Egypt away from its alliance with the Soviet Union.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1971, the US had information that the Arab states were willing to implement another embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In July 1972, Sadat expelled all 16,000 of the Soviet military personnel in Egypt in a signal that he wanted better relations with the United States.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger was taken completely by surprise by Sadat's move, saying: "Why has he done me this favor?
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For Sadat, cost was no object as the money to buy Soviet arms came from Saudi Arabia.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time, Faisal promised Sadat that if it should come to war, Saudi Arabia would embargo oil to the West.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In April 1973, the Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani visited Washington to meet Kissinger and told him that King Faisal was becoming more and more unhappy with the United States, saying he wanted America to pressure Israel to return all the lands captured in the Six Day War of 1967.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In a later interview, Yamani accused Kissinger of not taking his warning seriously, saying all he did was to ask him not to speak anymore of this threat.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Angry at Kissinger, Yamani, in an interview with the *Washington Post* on April 19, 1973, warned that King Faisal was considering an oil embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the time, the general feeling in Washington was the Saudis were bluffing and nothing would come of their threat to impose an oil embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The fact that Faisal's ineffectual half brother King Saud had imposed a crippling oil embargo on Britain and France during the Suez War of 1956 was not considered an important precedent.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The CEOs of four of the United States' oil companies, after speaking with Faisal, arrived in Washington in May 1973 with the warning that Faisal was considerably tougher, more intelligent and more ruthless than his half-brother Saud whom he had deposed in 1964, and that his threats were serious.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger declined to meet the four CEOs.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an assessment done by Kissinger and his staff about the Middle East in the summer of 1973, the repeated statements by Sadat about waging *jihad* against Israel were dismissed as empty talk, while the warnings from King Faisal were likewise regarded as inconsequential.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1973, Nixon fired Rogers as Secretary of State and replaced him with Kissinger.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger later stated he had not been given enough time to know the Middle East, as he settled into the State Department's office at Foggy Bottom as Egypt and Syria attacked Israel on 6 October 1973.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Yom Kippur began when Egypt attacked the Bar Lev Line in the Sinai Peninsula and Syria launched an offensive in the Golan Heights, both of which had been occupied by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal of Saudi Arabia was supportive, and on 8 October 1973, he told two Egyptian envoys: "You have made us all proud.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the past we could not lift our heads up.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He promised to give to Egypt a quality of aid worth $200 million US dollars to assist with the war effort, and stated he was willing to use the "oil weapon" if necessary to support Egypt.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The war began during the height of the Watergate scandal; as such Nixon largely let Kissinger manage foreign policy as he, Nixon, was distracted by the scandal.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger promised Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir that the United States would replace its losses in equipment after the war.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon had ordered an arms lift to Israel on 12 October 1973, but Kissinger used the excuse of bureaucratic delays to limit the amount of weapons and ammunition sent to Israel.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Arab concept of the "peace of the brave", i.e. a victorious leader being magnanimous to his defeated opponents, meant there was a possibility that Sadat at least would make peace with Israel provided that the war ended in such a way that Egypt was not perceived to be defeated.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Likewise, Kissinger regarded Meir as being rather arrogant and believed that an armistice that ended the war in a manner that was not an unambiguous Israeli victory would make her more humble.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As both Syria and Egypt lost much equipment during the fighting, the Soviet Union began to fly new equipment in, starting on 12 October.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Soviet flights to Syria and Egypt were recorded by the British radar stations in Cyprus.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Though the Soviets were flying in an average of 60 flights per day, exaggerated accounts appeared in Western newspapers speaking of "one hundred flights per day".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At this point, both Nixon and Kissinger began to see the October War more in terms of the Cold War rather than Middle Eastern politics, both seeing the Soviet arms lifts to Egypt and Syria as a Soviet power play that required an American answer.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On October 12, 1973, US president Richard Nixon authorized Operation Nickel Grass, a strategic airlift to deliver weapons and supplies to Israel in order to replace its materiel losses.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The first American weapons to Israel arrived on 15 October 1973, and despite Nixon's orders the number of American planes flying into Tel Aviv were initially limited.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the first week of the war, the Israelis had halted the Syrian offensive in the Golan Heights and were pushing back the Syrians back towards Damascus.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Along the Suez canal, however, there was heavy fighting, with the Egyptians holding their own.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At an OPEC summit at the Sheraton Hotel in Kuwait City on 16 October 1973, it was announced the price of oil would go from $3.01 US dollars per barrel to $5.12 per barrel.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The news about the war on 16 October was grim from the Arab viewpoint, with the Syrians steadily being pushed back, while Israelis had opened a counter-offensive against the Egyptians and crossed the Great Bitter Lake.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Responses from stated representatives at the meeting were varied.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani stated, in a 1981 interview, that "[t]he king still wanted to give America a chance to stay out of the fighting.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] So we agreed to cut back production by just 5 percent per month.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A full embargo, we agreed, was something we would implement only if we felt that things were absolutely hopeless".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Iranian delegation left the summit after agreeing to the price increase, as the Shah of Iran only supported higher oil prices.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Oil Minister of Iraq, Sa'dun Hammadi demanded the "total nationalization" of all assets of American oil companies in the Middle East, the withdrawal of all Arab funds from the United States and for all Arab states to break diplomatic relations with the United States.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Libyan Oil Minister, Izz al-Din al-Mabruk, called for the nationalization of all the assets of all Western oil companies in the Middle East.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudi delegation led by Yemani, supported by the Algerian delegation, fought hard against the Iraqi and Libyan demands for an embargo, as Yemani maintained that forcing through an increase in the price of oil was the best way to influence the United States.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Hammadi and the rest of the Iraqi delegation left upset as Yemani had won over the majority of the delegations to the Saudi viewpoint.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The statement issued after midnight at the Sheraton Hotel was handwritten and, reflecting the tense talk, had several paragraphs crossed out while other paragraphs were written in by different hands.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17 October, Arab oil producers cut production by 5% and threatened an oil embargo against Israel's wartime allies: the United States, the Netherlands, Rhodesia, South Africa, and Portugal.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17–19 October 1973, the Saudi Foreign Minister, Omar Al Saqqaf, visited Washington together with the foreign ministers of Algeria, Kuwait and Morocco to warn that there was a real possibility of an oil embargo being imposed.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon promised him that the United States would mediate a settlement to the war that would be "peaceful, just and honorable" to both sides.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He had ended the Vietnam war on what he felt was an honorable basis and now intended to end the October war in the same manner.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saqqaf complained to King Faisal that Nixon seemed more interested in a dispute about "a burglary" (i.e. the Watergate scandal) than about the war.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a press conference, an American reporter mocked the threat of an embargo, contemptuously saying the Saudis "could drink their oil", leading Saqqaf to reply in anger "All right, we will!".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Israel took heavy losses in men and materiel during the fighting against Egypt and Syria, and on 18 October 1973, Meir requested $850 million worth of American arms and equipment to replace its materiel losses.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon decided, characteristically, to act on an epic scale; Instead of the $850 million worth of arms requested, he sent a request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms to Israel, which was promptly approved.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon, whose administration was being badly battered by the Watergate scandal, felt that a bold foreign policy move might resuscitate his administration.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an interview with the British historian Robert Lacey in 1981, Kissinger later admitted about the arms lift to Israel: "I made a mistake.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In retrospect it was not the best considered decision we made".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The arms lift enraged King Faisal of Saudi Arabia.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was angry that Israel had only asked for $850 million worth of American weapons, and instead received an unsolicited $2.2 billion worth of weapons, which he perceived as a sign of the pro-Israeli slant of American foreign policy.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal also felt insulted that Nixon had just promised Saqqaf an "honorable" peace the day before he submitted the request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms for Israel, which he saw as an act of duplicity on Nixon's part.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal had been opposed to a total embargo and only agreed to the 5% cut on 17 October under pressure from other Arab states.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal felt his efforts on behalf the United States were not being appreciated in Washington, which increased his fury at Nixon.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the afternoon of 19 October 1973, Faisal was in his office when he learned about the United States sending $2.2 billion worth of weapons to Israel, and discussed the issue with two of his closest advisers, Abdullah ibn Abdul Rahman and Rashad Pharaon.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king called Yamani at about 8 pm, and told him he was needed at the Riyassa Palace immediately.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Yamani told the king: "The TV news goes out at nine.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] If you make a decision now, we can get it announced at once".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king replied "Write this down" and announced he was placing a total embargo on the United States.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most of the other oil-producing Arab states joined the embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Algeria, Iraq, and Libya promoted the embargo, but did not actively enforce it.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo was accompanied by gradual monthly production cuts—by December, production had been cut to 25% of September levels.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This contributed to a global recession and increased tension between the United States and several of its European allies, who faulted the US for provoking an embargo by providing what many viewed as unconditional assistance to Israel.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC demanded a complete Israeli withdrawal from all territories beyond the 1949 Armistice border.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo lasted from October 1973 to March 1974.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because every Arab state except for Iraq and Libya joined the oil embargo, oil exports from the Middle East to the West were down by 60–70% by November 1973.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Japan and the nations of western Europe imported some 75% of their oil from the Near East.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo led to immediate and sharp price raises, as Lacey noted that "competing desperately for dwindling supplies, consumers showed themselves willing to pay unparalleled money for their oil".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil reserves.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo imposed on the United States led to shortages of oil in the United States, which set an inflationary spiral, as the new high prices for oil in the American market led to sharp increases of the price of oil in nations not subjected to the embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When the Iranian state oil company held an auction on 16 December 1973, bids for some $17 US dollars per barrel of oil were made.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In late December 1973, OPEC held a conference in Vienna when it was announced the price for a barrel of oil was to increase from $5 US dollars per barrel to $11.65 US dollars per barrel.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was opposed to the price increase, which was largely the work of the Iranian delegation.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 22 February 1974, King Faisal chaired the second summit of Islamic states in Lahore, which, unlike the first summit that Faisal had chaired in 1969, was not boycotted by Iraq and Syria.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was acclaimed as a conquering hero who humiliated and humbled the West by wrecking its economy.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The prime minister of Pakistan, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, opened the conference by stating: "The armies of Pakistan are the armies of Islam.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On November 7, 1973, Kissinger flew to Riyadh to meet King Faisal and ask him to end the oil embargo in exchange for promising to be "evenhanded" with the Arab-Israeli dispute.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As the plane carrying him prepared to land in Riyadh, Kissinger was clearly nervous at the prospect of negotiating with the stern Wahhabi Faisal who had a marked dislike of Jews.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a summit in Cairo the day before, Kissinger asked Sadat what Faisal was like and was told: "Well, Dr.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Henry, he will probably go on with you about Communism and the Jews".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] King Faisal's two great hatreds were communism and Zionism, as he believed that the Soviet Union and Israel were plotting together against Islam.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Initially, Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger suggested to Kissinger that the USA invade Saudi Arabia and another Arab countries and seize their oil fields.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger stated in a private state department meeting that it's “ridiculous that the civilized world is held up by 8 million savages...
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Can’t we overthrow one of the sheikhs just to show that we can do it?” They formed a plan to invade Abu Dhabi, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger publicly threatened "countermeasures" in a November 21, 1973 press conference if the embargo was not lifted, and the Saudis responded with threatening further oil cuts and to burn their oil fields if the US military invaded.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the CIA confirmed these threats, Kissinger gave up military intervention and decided to deal with Israel's troop withdrawals, settling on diplomatic solutions to the oil embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 18 March 1974, King Faisal ended the oil embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat had reported to Faisal that the United States was being more "evenhanded", and Kissinger had promised to sell Saudi Arabia weapons that it had previously denied under the grounds that they might be used against Israel.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Since Israeli forces did not withdraw to the 1949 Armistice Line, the majority of scholars believe that the embargo was a failure.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Roy Licklieder, in his 1988 book *Political Power and the Arab Oil Weapon*, concluded that the embargo was a failure because the countries that were targeted by the embargo did not change their policies on the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Licklieder believed that any long term changes were caused by the OPEC increase in the posted price of oil, and not the OAPEC embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Daniel Yergin, on the other hand, has said that the embargo "remade the international economy".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Over the long term, the oil embargo changed the nature of policy in the West towards increased exploration, alternative energy research, energy conservation and more restrictive monetary policy to better fight inflation.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For further details see the "Energy crisis" series by Facts on File.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The effects of the embargo were immediate.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC forced oil companies to increase payments drastically.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price of oil quadrupled by 1974 from US$3 to nearly US$12 per 42 gallon barrel ($75 per cubic meter), equivalent in 2018 dollars to a price rise from $17 to $61 per barrel.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil, but only 4% of the oil used in the United States in 1973 came from the kingdom.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, Saudi Arabia plays an over-sized role within the Arab world.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, about 25% of the oil used in the United States came from Arab countries.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The shortage of oil within the United States caused by the Arab oil embargo forced prices to rise, which led price rises globally.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oil producers that had not joined the embargo such as Iran, Venezuela, Libya and Iraq demanded higher prices in Japan and Europe, as an initiative to ship oil to those places instead of the United States, setting off a worldwide inflationary spiral.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Although the embargo did not severely disrupt US oil supplies—since Americans imported more oil from non-embargoed nations such as Iran—the resulting 400% increase in oil prices caused by the embargo damaged the American economy.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of nations such as Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran and Iraq increased their oil production during the embargo, and sold their oil at a higher price.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader who pushed the most for higher oil prices was the Shah of Iran, and the Italian historian Giuliano Garavini has argued that the leader most responsible for the West's economic problems during the "oil shock" was not King Faisal, but rather the Shah.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the nations that were classified as "friendly" to the Arab viewpoint in regards to the Arab-Israeli dispute such as France and Belgium were the ones who suffered the most from the worldwide inflation caused by the embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In March 1974, the crisis eased when the embargo was lifted after negotiations at the Washington Oil Summit, but the effects lingered throughout the 1970s.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The dollar price of energy increased again in 1975, amid the weakening competitive position of the dollar in world markets.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Arab oil embargo ended the long period of prosperity in the West that had begun in 1945, throwing the world's economy into the steepest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "long summer" of prosperity in the post-war years had made possible the "swinging sixties" and the related rise of a rebellious youth culture, as it was easy to be hedonist or in rebellion against traditional values in a time of unprecedented prosperity.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 1945 to 1973 had been a period of unprecedented prosperity in the West, a "long summer" that many believed would never end.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Its abrupt end in 1973, as the oil embargo increased the price of oil by 400% within a matter of days and threw the world's economy into a sharp recession, with unemployment mounting and inflation raging, came as a profound shock.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The end of what the French called the *Trente Glorieuses* ("Glorious Thirty" [years]) led to widespread pessimism in the West, with the *Financial Times* running a famous headline in late 1973 saying, "The Future will be subject to Delay".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In an August 1974 address to the General Assembly, Kurt Waldheim, the secretary-general of the United Nations, complained about "the note of helplessness and fatalism creeping into world affairs".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The sudden and abrupt end of the "long summer" of prosperity in 1973-1974 played a major role in the pessimistic mood that characterized the culture of the West of the 1970s.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1975, a report to Congress from the Federal Energy Administration estimated that the embargo of 1973–1974 had caused about 500,000 Americans to lose their jobs, and caused a GNP loss between $10 billion–$20 billion.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This price increase had a dramatic effect on oil exporting nations, for the countries of the Middle East who had long been dominated by the industrial powers were seen to have taken control of a vital commodity.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil-exporting nations began to accumulate vast wealth.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the income was dispensed in the form of aid to other underdeveloped nations whose economies had been caught between higher oil prices and lower prices for their own export commodities, amid shrinking Western demand.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much went for arms purchases that exacerbated political tensions, particularly in the Middle East.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The 400% increase in the world oil prices led to extravagant promises being made by the leaders of oil-producing nations.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Shah of Iran told his subjects in a speech in December 1973 that he was launching "Great Civilization" project that would make Iran into a First World nation by the 1990s.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Carlos Andrés Pérez of Venezuela likewise launched his *Le Gran Venezuela* project intended to make Venezuela into a First World nation.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Yakubu Gowon of Nigeria told his people that henceforward Nigeria's main problem would be "managing abundance".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] After the oil shock, Nigeria presented itself as the first African nation that would reach First World status.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Lagos, a series of stately modernist buildings were erected as appropriate for a nation that saw itself as the leader of all Black Africa.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much of the oil wealth in Nigeria was stolen by corrupt politicians.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At least some of Nigeria's new oil wealth went to rebuild the areas devastated by the civil war of 1967-1970 and to address the complaints that too much of Nigeria's oil wealth went to the federal government in Lagos instead of the people.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new wealth generated by the "oil shock" allowed for Chairman Houari Boumédiène of Algeria to become a global leader, courted by elites in the First World and the Third World.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil embargo led a sudden interest in the Palestinian issue.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Between 1973 and 1981, Saudi Arabia donated a sum worth $1 billion US dollars to the Palestine Liberation Organization, which thus had a budget that exceeded that of many Third World nations.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On November 8, 1973, Kissinger became the first Secretary of State to meet with a Saudi leader since 1953, as he met King Faisal to ask him to end the embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Within two week of the embargo being launched, all of the foreign ministers of the nations of the European Economic Community, now the European Union, met in a conference to issue a statement calling for Israel "to end the territorial occupation which has maintained since the conflict of 1967".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On December 11, 1973, the Japanese Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ōhira flew in to Riyadh to meet King Faisal for "talks on improving bilateral relations".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Shortly afterwards, the French foreign minister Michel Jobert arrived to sign an agreement that provided oil for France for the next twenty years.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On January 24, 1974, as the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was coming off the ski slopes of St.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moritz, he was met by the British Chancellor of Exchequer, Anthony Barber, and the Trade Secretary, Peter Walker.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a role-reversal, Barber and Walker paid homage to the Shah, who promised them that his nation would sell the United Kingdom 5 million tons of oil in exchange for some £100 million of British goods, to aid his plans to industrialize Iran.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia experienced an upsurge of prosperity and affluence after the oil embargo, whose consequences horrified King Faisal.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal, who was devoted to a harsh puritanical strain of Sunni Islam known in the West as Wahhabism, was appalled by the way that his subjects became materialistic, devoted only to conspicuous consumption and greed as they lost interest in Islam.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Lacey wrote: "The spiritual dangers of easy affluence distressed him more.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His simple gesture of piety and honor seemed to have opened a Pandora's Box that threatened to turn his realm into a parody of all he held dear".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the last two of years of his life, Faisal fell into depression over the way his subjects had been seduced into a consumerist lifestyle, becoming lost in a sense of "melancholia".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal's son, Crown Prince Mohammad told Lacey in 1981: "The profligacy, the greed, he felt he could not stem it.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] He become so bound up in his work, there was almost nothing private of him left".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A sign of the changed values was that despite the total ban on alcohol in Saudi Arabia, drinking and drug use became common with the younger members of the House of Saud.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] James Akins, the American ambassador in Riyadh reported; "the sky over Riyadh is black with vultures with new get-richer-quicker plans under their wings".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1974, property prices in Riyadh doubled on a weekly basis for the entire year, as the prosperity led to a real estate speculation bubble that was often compared to the Klondike gold rush of 1898–1899.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At the Red Sea port of Jeddah, there were so many ships queuing up laden with cement for the construction boom in Saudi Arabia, that construction contractors hired helicopters to fly the cement in, twenty bags per flight.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of families engaged in the Saudi construction industry such as the Juffali, Alireza, al-Khasshoggi and the bin Laden families all became very wealthy as a result of the construction boom.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The period after the oil shock of 1973–1974 is still fondly remembered in Saudi Arabia as the "age of abundance", where nearly everyone had a significant increase in their standard of living.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The wealth and corruption generated by the oil shock led to a fundamentalist backlash in Saudi Arabia.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 20 November 1979, Islam's holiest shrine, the Grand Mosque of Mecca, was seized by a group who proclaimed themselves to be the followers of the Mahdi, a messianic figure said to appear at the dawn of every Muslim century to strike down the enemies of Islam.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader of the uprising, Juhayman al-Otaybi, read out a list of grievances, as he accused the House of Saud of being corrupt and degenerate, listing by name a number of Saudi princes who were engaged in dubious business dealings and/or who drank alcohol.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Saudi Army recaptured the Grand Mosque, and the surviving "renegades", as the rebels were labelled, were executed.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Algeria, the "oil shock" led to the establishment of a welfare state where none had existed previously.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The lower oil prices of the 1980s along with cutbacks and the belief that the FLN regime was corrupt helped cause the riots of October 1988 against the FLN regime, that killed at least 500 people.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The riots were largely caused by the fact that the low oil prices had forced the Algerian state to end many of its more generous social policies between 1986 and 1988, leading to an unemployment rate of 30% by 1988, along with the knowledge that the FLN regime had stolen millions.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the aftermath of the October riots, President Chadli Bendjedid began a transition to democracy.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The first free elections in Algeria in January 1992 were won by the Islamist FIS, which led to a military coup and an outbreak of a civil war that killed hundreds of thousands of Algerians.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC-member states raised the prospect of nationalization of oil company holdings.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Most notably, Saudi Arabia nationalized Aramco in 1980 under the leadership of Saudi oil minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As other OPEC nations followed suit, the cartel's income soared.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia undertook a series of ambitious five-year development plans.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The biggest began in 1980, funded at $250 billion.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Other cartel members also undertook major economic development programs.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Control of oil became known as the "oil weapon".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It came in the form of an embargo and production cutbacks from the Arab states.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The weapon was aimed at the United States, Great Britain, Canada, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] These target governments perceived that the intent was to push them towards a more pro-Arab position.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, the affected countries did not undertake dramatic policy changes.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The risk that the Middle East could become another superpower confrontation with the USSR was of more concern to Washington than oil.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Further, interest groups and government agencies more worried about energy were no match for Kissinger's dominance.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo had a negative influence on the US economy, causing immediate demands to address the threats to US energy security.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On an international level, the price increases changed competitive positions in many industries, such as automobiles.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Macroeconomic problems consisted of both inflationary and deflationary impacts.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo left oil companies searching for new ways to increase oil supplies, even in rugged terrain such as the Arctic.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Finding oil and developing new fields usually required five to 10 years before significant production.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The average US retail price of a gallon of regular gasoline rose 43% from 38.5¢ in May 1973 to 55.1¢ in June 1974.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] State governments asked citizens not to put up Christmas lights.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oregon banned Christmas and commercial lighting altogether.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Politicians called for a national gasoline rationing program.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon asked gasoline retailers to voluntarily not sell gasoline on Saturday nights or Sundays.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 90% of gas station owners complied, which produced long lines of motorists wanting to fill up their cars while they still could.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "oil shock" provided considerable impetus to the American nuclear industry as a way to achieve "energy independence" from the Middle East.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 7 November 1973, Nixon in an address to Congress called for Project Independence to make the United States self-sufficient in energy by 1980, which called for a massive investment in the nuclear industry.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon envisioned nuclear energy as more economical, and was encouraged by the enthusiasm of many officials who saw nuclear energy as the technology of the future.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the late 1960s, a lively environmentalist movement had emerged in the United States, and the Project Independence nuclear program was the subject of much debate in both the media and Congress.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The ensuing debates revealed that many of the claims made for nuclear power underestimated the true costs of nuclear reactors.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Equally problematic was where to safety store the spent nuclear rods that emitted a toxic level of radioactivity for centuries afterward, in a cost-effective manner.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The issue of the spent nuclear rods was especially difficult because of NIMBYism, where communities proved unwilling to accept a storage place for the inevitable by-product of nuclear power, the spent nuclear rods, with the demand that the government find some other community to store the rods.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Many of the nuclear reactors ordered in 1973 were cancelled due to cost overruns, while over 100 nuclear plants were shut down as uneconomical over the next 10 years.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike nations that tried to use nuclear power as a way for energy independence such as France and Sweden, the United States had substantial reserves of its own oil, which weakened the case for nuclear power in the ensuring debates.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By 1989, only 18% of American energy came from nuclear power plants, which was a fraction of what Project Independence had envisioned in 1973.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock led to anti-Arab feelings becoming common.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Cartoons published in American newspapers during the oil shock depicted Arabs as disgusting, ugly, obese, corrupt and greedy.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the cartoons, the long hooked Semitic noses that had traditionally been featured in anti-Jewish cartoons were applied to the Arab sheiks as a way to illustrate their supposed greed.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] American public opinion did not see the use of the "oil weapon" as due to politics, and tended to explain the embargo as only due to the excessive greed of King Faisal and the other Arab leaders, hence the use of the hooked Semitic nose in the cartoons as a sort of shorthand for insatiable greed.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soviet Union was not a beneficiary of the oil crisis.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis prompted the USSR to raise energy prices within the Council on Mutual Economic Assistance (CMEA).
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo was not uniform across Western Europe.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Of the nine members of the European Economic Community (EEC), the Netherlands faced a complete embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By contrast Britain and France received almost uninterrupted supplies.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] That was their reward for refusing to allow the US to use their airfields and stopping arms and supplies to both the Arabs and the Israelis.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other six EEC nations faced partial cutbacks.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK had traditionally been an ally of Israel, and Harold Wilson's government supported the Israelis during the Six-Day War.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His successor, Ted Heath, reversed this policy in 1970, calling for Israel to withdraw to its pre-1967 borders.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc made imports more expensive for French consumers, which encouraged them to buy French products, while making French products cheaper abroad.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] France was entirely dependent upon imported oil, through French companies continued to lease the oil concessions in Algeria until 1971.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The low price of oil internationally compensated to a certain extent for the higher price of oil caused by the devaluation.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc ensured that the dramatic price increases caused by the oil shock hit the French economy especially hard in 1973.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland and Norway banned flying, driving and boating on Sundays.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The EEC was unable to achieve a common policy during the first month of the embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It issued a statement on November 6, after the embargo and price rises had begun.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It was widely viewed as pro-Arab, supporting the Franco-British line on the war.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC duly lifted its embargo from all EEC members.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other European states did not rally in defense of the Dutch who were left to fend for themselves and instead reached bilateral deals with Saudi Arabia, Iraq and Iran.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faced with a recession, there was a tendency within the EEC nations to turn inwards away from European integration.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price rises had a much greater impact in Europe than the embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis retarded the movement towards European economic integration which had been gathering pace ever since the EEC, now the European Union, had been founded in 1957.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, the German historian Jens-Uwe Wunderlich wrote that attempts to finish off the European common market came to a "complete standstill" in 1973 and it was not until 1977 that movement towards creating the common market resumed.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In particular, the oil shock increased the appeal of nuclear energy as a way to achieve energy independence from the turbulent Middle East.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Starting in March 1974 with the "Energy Plan" introduced by the premier Pierre Messmer, the French state made a massive investment in nuclear energy.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the 1990s, 80% of all of France's energy came from nuclear plants.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The North Sea oil fields, which were discovered in 1969, did not start to be exploited until 1975, making the United Kingdom entirely dependent upon imported oil in 1973.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The way that world oil prices quadrupled in late 1973 had a very adverse impact on the British economy,.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a series of speeches in December 1973, the Prime Minister Edward Heath warned that because of the oil shock that the British economy was going into recession and the British people should expect economic austerity.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Heath offered the coal miners a 7% wage increase, which was rejected as insufficient by the miners who went on strike.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Through not subjected to the embargo, the UK faced an energy crisis of its own—a series of strikes by coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the defeat of Heath's Conservative government in the February 1974 general elections.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new Labour government told the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Labour government of Harold Wilson settled the strike by giving the coal miners a 35% pay increase.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan was hard hit, since it imported 90% of its oil from the Middle East.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It had a stockpile good for 55 days, and another 20-day supply was en route.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Facing its most serious crisis since 1945, the government ordered a 10% cut in the consumption of industrial oil and electricity.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, it ordered an immediate 20% cut in oil use and electric power to Japan's major industries, and cutbacks in leisure automobile usage.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Economist predicted the growth rate would plunge from 5% annually, down to zero or even negative territory.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Seeking to take advantage of the crisis, Japanese business called on the government to relax its controls on air pollution and water pollution.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moscow tried to take advantage by promising energy assistance if Japan renounced its claim to the Kurile Islands.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Instead it made $3.3 billion of dollars in loans to the Arab states and called on Israel to step back.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan's defensive strategy was explained to Kissinger when he met with top leaders in Tokyo in November 1973.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the long run Japan never wavered in its determination to maintain very strong close ties to the United States, while in self-defense briefly providing the Arab powers with the rhetoric they demanded in return for resuming oil shipments in early 1974.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] To assure future oil flows, Japan added suppliers outside of the Middle East, invested in nuclear power, imposed conservation measures, and provided funding for Arab governments and the Palestinians.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis was a major factor in the long-run shift of Japan's economy away from oil-intensive industries.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japanese auto makers benefited from the crisis.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The jump in gasoline prices helped their small, fuel-efficient models to gain market share from the "gas-guzzling" Detroit competition.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This triggered a drop in US sales of American cars that lasted into the 1980s.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil crisis contributed to the poor state of the Indian economy and played a role in Indira Gandhi's decision to impose The Emergency, a dictatorship.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The state led a push for coal as an energy source, even though there were reservations about its adverse environmental effects.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock destroyed the economy of South Vietnam.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A spokesman for President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu admitted in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation caused by the oil shock.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] An American businessman living in Saigon stated after the oil shock, that attempting to make money in South Vietnam was "like making love to a corpse".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, Vietcong sappers attacked and destroyed the petroleum depot of Nha Be, further depleting fuel sources.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the summer of 1974, the US embassy in Saigon reported that morale in the ARVN (Army of the Republic of Vietnam) had fallen to dangerously low levels and it was uncertain how much more longer South Vietnam would last.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As inflation eroded the value of the South Vietnamese *đồng*, it became common by the summer of 1974 to see ARVN soldiers and their families begging in the streets for food.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1974, the North Vietnamese PAVN (People's Army of Vietnam) launched an offensive in the Central Highlands that was far more successful than expected, due to the ARVN's low morale and weak resistance.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On March 1, 1975, the PAVN launched a major offensive that quickly overran the Central Highlands.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Following their victory in the Central Highlands, the North Vietnamese launched the "Ho Chi Minh Campaign" that captured Saigon on April 30, 1975.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Three of the nations targeted by the embargo were located in southern Africa or had colonies there.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal which ruled the colonies of Angola, Portuguese Guiana (modern Guinea-Bissau), and Portuguese East Africa (modern Mozambique) had fighting colonial wars in all of its African colonies since the 1960s with Angola being the first to rise up in 1961.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Angola is rich in oil, which protected Portugal from the worse of the embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] But the economic stability of the *Estado Novo* regime was damaged by the worldwide inflation, which help cause the Carnation Revolution which toppled the *Estado Novo* regime in April 1974 and led to the restoration of democracy.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal granted independence to all of its colonies except for Macau in 1975.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The British historian Rob Skinner wrote the embargo had a "significant impact" on the South African economy.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The inflationary rise in commodity prices increased the input costs of South African manufacturing, making South African manufactured goods uncompetitive on the world market.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The rise in the price of gold as a hedge against inflation (South Africa has the world's largest gold mines) caused the *rand* to increase in value, which caused further problems for South African manufacturing.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The strategy pursued by the National Party government since 1948 of sponsoring the industrialization of South Africa was derailed by the oil shock, with what Skinner described as "important social and political consequences" for the *apartheid* regime.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soweto uprising of 1976 was at least in part caused by anger at the high unemployment rate in the black South African community.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Even worse hit than South Africa was Rhodesia (modern Zimbabwe), where oil was already expensive as the white supremacist government of Rhodesia had been under United Nations sanctions since 1965, and thus the smugglers who sold Rhodesia oil charged a premium for their services.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The premium charged by the "sanctions busters" such as Iran increased after the embargo, which threw the Rhodesian economy into recession.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Despite the United Nations sanctions, Rhodesia was a major exporter of chrome, steel and tobacco with the United States exempting "strategical" Rhodesian products such as chrome from the sanctions.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The global recession of 1973–1975 proved more effective than the United Nations in ending the global demand for Rhodesian products, which made the Rhodesian recession especially severe.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike South Africa, which had a sizable and long-standing white population, the white population of Rhodesia was much smaller and more recent.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Rhodesia depended considerably more than South Africa on white immigration to provide enough soldiers for its army, while most of the Rhodesian whites had only arrived in the 1950s and did not have very deep roots in the country.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The white flight caused by the recession put the Rhodesian Army at a major disadvantage in its war against the black guerrillas.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The war cost the Rhodesian government one million Rhodesian dollars per day by 1975, and the costs of the war threatened to bankrupt Rhodesia.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1979, Rhodesia signed the Lancaster House Agreement, which led to Black majority rule in 1980.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The system limited the price of "old oil", that which had already been discovered, while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price, to encourage investment.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a result, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Scarcity was addressed by rationing, as in many countries.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A sign of the change caused by the crisis was that in 1974 the Exxon oil company replaced the General Motors corporation to be the largest corporation in the world, as measured by gross sales revenues.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon as the first Administrator of the Federal Energy Office, a short-term organization created to coordinate the response to the embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon allocated states the same amount of domestic oil for 1974 that each had consumed in 1972, which worked for states whose populations were not increasing.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In other states, lines at gasoline stations were common.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The American Automobile Association reported that in the last week of February 1974, 20% of American gasoline stations had no fuel.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Odd–even rationing allowed vehicles with license plates having an odd number as the last digit, or a vanity license plate, to buy gas only on odd-numbered days of the month.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Others could buy only on even-numbered days.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In some states, a three-color flag system was used to denote gasoline availability at service stations—green for unrationed availability, yellow for restricted/rationed sales, and red for out of stock.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Rationing led to violent incidents, when truck drivers chose to strike for two days in December 1973 over the limited supplies that Simon had allocated for their industry.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Pennsylvania and Ohio, non-striking truckers were shot at by striking truckers.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Arkansas, trucks of non-strikers were attacked with bombs.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America had controlled the price of natural gas since the 1950s.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the inflation of the 1970s, the price was too low to encourage the search for new reserves.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's natural gas reserves dwindled from 237 trillion in 1974 to 203 trillion in 1978.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price controls were not changed, despite president Gerald Ford's repeated requests to Congress.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (89 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In November 1995, President Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph speed limit, which allowed states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Year-round daylight saving time was implemented from January 6, 1974, to October 27, 1975, with a break between October 27, 1974, and February 23, 1975, when the country observed standard time.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Parents complained that it forced many children to travel to school before sunrise.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis prompted a call to conserve energy, most notably a campaign by the Advertising Council using the tagline "Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Many newspapers carried advertisements featuring cut-outs that could be attached to light switches, reading "Last Out, Lights Out: Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although not regulated by the new legislation, auto racing groups voluntarily began conserving.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1974, NASCAR reduced all race distances by 10%; the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring race were cancelled.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1975, the Energy Policy and Conservation Act was passed, leading to the creation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards that required improved fuel economy for cars and light trucks.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Congress created the Weatherization Assistance Program to help low-income homeowners and renters reduce their demand for heating and cooling through better insulation.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, domestic luxury cars with a 130-inch (3.3 m) wheelbase and gross weights averaging 4,500 pounds (2,041 kg) were no longer made.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The automakers had begun phasing out the traditional front engine/rear-wheel drive layout in compact cars in favor of lighter front engine/front-wheel drive designs.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A higher percentage of cars offered more efficient four-cylinder engines.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Domestic auto makers also began offering more fuel efficient diesel powered passenger cars as well.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The energy crisis led to greater interest in renewable energy, nuclear power and domestic fossil fuels.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2013, Peter Grossman opined that American energy policies after the crisis became and remained dominated by crisis-mentality thinking, promoting expensive quick fixes and single-shot solutions that ignore market and technology realities.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] He wrote that instead of providing stable rules that support basic research while leaving plenty of scope for entrepreneurship and innovation, Congresses and presidents repeatedly backed policies which promised politically expedient solutions whose true prospects were doubtful.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Brazilian government implemented its Proálcool (pro-alcohol) project in 1975 that mixed ethanol with gasoline for automotive fuel.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Israel was one of the few countries unaffected by the embargo, since it could extract sufficient oil from the Sinai.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] But to supplement Israel's over-taxed power grid, Harry Zvi Tabor, the father of Israel's solar industry, developed the prototype for a solar water heater now used in over 90% of Israeli homes.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western central banks decided to sharply cut interest rates to encourage growth, deciding that inflation was a secondary concern.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although this was the orthodox macroeconomic prescription at the time, the resulting stagflation surprised economists and central bankers.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The policy is now considered by some to have deepened and lengthened the adverse effects of the embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Recent research claims that in the period after 1985 the economy became more resilient to energy price increases.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price shock created large current account deficits in oil-importing economies.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A petrodollar recycling mechanism was created, through which OPEC surplus funds were channeled through the capital markets to the West to finance the current account deficits.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The functioning of this mechanism required the relaxation of capital controls in oil-importing economies.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It marked the beginning of an exponential growth of Western capital markets.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the United States in 1974, seven of the 15 top Fortune 500 companies were oil companies, falling to four in 2014.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis had a major impact on international relations and created a rift within NATO.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some European nations and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from United States foreign policy in the Middle East to avoid being targeted by the boycott.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Arab oil producers linked any future policy changes to peace between the belligerents.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To address this, the Nixon Administration began multilateral negotiations with the combatants.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They arranged for Israel to pull back from the Sinai Peninsula and the Golan Heights.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By January 18, 1974, US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was enough to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974. and again during the 1979 energy crisis.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's Cold War policies suffered a major blow from the embargo.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They had focused on China and the Soviet Union, but the latent challenge to US hegemony coming from the Third World became evident.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2004, declassified documents revealed that the US was so distraught by the rise in oil prices and being challenged by underdeveloped countries that they briefly considered military action to forcibly seize Middle Eastern oilfields in late 1973.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western Europe began switching from pro-Israel to more pro-Arab policies.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This change strained the Western alliance.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The US, which imported only 12% of its oil from the Middle East (compared with 80% for the Europeans and over 90% for Japan), remained staunchly committed to Israel.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The percentage of US oil which comes from the nations bordering the Persian Gulf remained steady over the decades, with a figure of a little more than 10% in 2008.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the embargo in place, many developed countries altered their policies regarding the Arab-Israeli conflict.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These included the UK, which refused to allow the United States to use British bases and Cyprus to airlift resupplies to Israel, along with the rest of the members of the European Community.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Canada shifted towards a more pro-Arab position after displeasure was expressed towards Canada's mostly neutral position.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] "On the other hand, after the embargo the Canadian government moved quickly indeed toward the Arab position, despite its low dependence on Middle Eastern oil".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although lacking historical connections to the Middle East, Japan was the country most dependent on Arab oil.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] 71% of its imported oil came from the Middle East in 1970.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 7, 1973, the Saudi and Kuwaiti governments declared Japan a "nonfriendly" country, to encourage it to change its noninvolvement policy.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It received a 5% production cut in December, causing a panic.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 22, Japan issued a statement "asserting that Israel should withdraw from all of the 1967 territories, advocating Palestinian self-determination, and threatening to reconsider its policy toward Israel if Israel refused to accept these preconditions".
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By December 25, Japan was considered an Arab-friendly state.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil embargo was announced roughly one month after a right-wing military coup in Chile led by General Augusto Pinochet toppled socialist president Salvador Allende on September 11, 1973.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The response of the Nixon administration was to propose doubling arms sales.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, an opposing Latin American bloc was organized and financed in part by Venezuelan oil revenues, which quadrupled between 1970 and 1975.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil shock disrupted the status quo relationships between Arab countries and the US and USSR.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] At the time, Egypt, Syria and Iraq were allied with the USSR.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Iran, plus Israel, aligned with the US.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Vacillations in alignment often resulted in greater support from the respective superpowers.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When Anwar Sadat became president of Egypt in 1970, he dismissed Soviet specialists in Egypt and reoriented towards the US.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Concerns over economic domination from increased Soviet oil production turned into fears of military aggression after the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, a major turning point in Cold War geopolitics.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Persian Gulf states turned toward the US for security guarantees against Soviet military action, coming at a time marked by increased American weapons sales, technology, and outright military presence to various US-allied nations.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia and Iran became increasingly dependent on American security assurances to manage both external and internal threats, including increased military competition between them over increased oil revenues.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Both states were competing for preeminence in the Persian Gulf, and using increased revenues to fund expanded militaries.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, Saudi arms purchases from the US were five times larger than Israel's.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia is a near-absolute monarchy, an Arabic speaking country, and has a Sunni Muslim majority, while Persian speaking Iran since 1979 is an Islamist theocracy with a Shiite Muslim majority, which explains the current hostility between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis sent a signal to the auto industry globally, which changed many aspects of production and usage for decades to come.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] After World War II, most West European countries taxed motor fuel to limit imports, and as a result most cars made in Europe were smaller and more economical than their American counterparts.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the late 1960s, increasing incomes supported rising car sizes.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis pushed West European car buyers away from larger, less economical cars.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The most notable result of this transition was the rise in popularity of compact hatchbacks.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only notable small hatchbacks built in Western Europe before the oil crisis were the Peugeot 104, Renault 5 and Fiat 127.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the end of the decade, the market had expanded with the introduction of the Ford Fiesta, Opel Kadett (sold as the Vauxhall Astra in Great Britain), Chrysler Sunbeam and Citroën Visa.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Buyers looking for larger cars were increasingly drawn to medium-sized hatchbacks.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Virtually unknown in Europe in 1973, by the end of the decade they were gradually replacing sedans as the mainstay of this sector.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Between 1973 and 1980, medium-sized hatchbacks were launched across Europe: the Chrysler/Simca Horizon, Fiat Ritmo (Strada in the UK), Ford Escort MK3, Renault 14, Volvo 340 / 360, Opel Kadett, and Volkswagen Golf.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These cars were considerably more economical than the traditional saloons they were replacing, and attracted buyers who traditionally bought larger vehicles.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some 15 years after the oil crisis, hatchbacks dominated most European small and medium car markets, and had gained a substantial share of the large family car market.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Before the energy crisis, large, heavy, and powerful cars were popular.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1971, the standard engine in a Chevrolet Caprice was a 400-cubic inch (6.5 liter) V8.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The wheelbase of this car was 121.5 inches (3,090 mm), and *Motor Trend*'s 1972 road test of the similar Chevrolet Impala achieved no more than 15 highway miles per gallon.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the 15 years prior to the 1973 oil crisis, gasoline prices in the US had lagged well behind inflation.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis reduced the demand for large cars.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Japanese imports became mass-market leaders with unibody construction and front-wheel drive, which became de facto standards.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] From Europe, the Volkswagen Beetle, the Volkswagen Fastback, the Renault 8, the Renault LeCar, and the Fiat Brava were successful.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Detroit responded with the Ford Pinto, the Ford Maverick, the Chevrolet Vega, the Chevrolet Nova, the Plymouth Valiant and the Plymouth Volaré.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] American Motors sold its homegrown Gremlin, Hornet and Pacer models.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A decade after the 1973 oil crisis, Honda, Toyota and Nissan, affected by the 1981 voluntary export restraints, opened US assembly plants and established their luxury divisions (Acura, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively) to distinguish themselves from their mass-market brands.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Compact trucks were introduced, such as the Toyota Hilux and the Datsun Truck, followed by the Mazda Truck (sold as the Ford Courier), and the Isuzu-built Chevrolet LUV.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mitsubishi rebranded its Forte as the Dodge D-50 a few years after the oil crisis.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mazda, Mitsubishi and Isuzu had joint partnerships with Ford, Chrysler, and GM, respectively.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Later, the American makers introduced their domestic replacements (Ford Ranger, Dodge Dakota and the Chevrolet S10/GMC S-15), ending their captive import policy.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] An increase in imported cars into North America forced General Motors, Ford and Chrysler to introduce smaller and fuel-efficient models for domestic sales.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Dodge Omni / Plymouth Horizon from Chrysler, the Ford Fiesta and the Chevrolet Chevette all had four-cylinder engines and room for at least four passengers by the late 1970s.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1985, the average American vehicle moved 17.4 miles per gallon, compared to 13.5 in 1970.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The improvements stayed, even though the price of a barrel of oil remained constant at $12 from 1974 to 1979.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Sales of large sedans for most makes, except Chrysler products, recovered within two model years of the 1973 crisis.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Cadillac DeVille and Fleetwood, Buick Electra, Oldsmobile 98, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Marquis, and various other luxury oriented sedans became popular again in the mid-1970s.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only full-size models that did not recover were lower price models such as the Chevrolet Bel Air and Ford Galaxie 500.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Slightly smaller models such as the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Ford Thunderbird and various others sold well.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Economical imports succeeded alongside heavy, expensive vehicles.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Toyota sold 346,920 cars (average weight around 2,100 lbs), while Cadillac sold 309,139 cars (average weight around 5,000 lbs).
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Federal safety standards, such as NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 215 (pertaining to safety bumpers), and compacts like the 1974 Mustang I were a prelude to the DOT "downsize" revision of vehicle categories.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1977, GM's full-sized cars reflected the crisis.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, virtually all "full-size" American cars had shrunk, featuring smaller engines and smaller outside dimensions.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Chrysler ended production of their full-sized luxury sedans at the end of the 1981 model year, moving instead to a full front-wheel drive lineup for 1982, except for the M-body Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury and Chrysler New Yorker Fifth Avenue sedans.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC soon lost its preeminent position, and in 1981, its production was surpassed by that of other countries.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Additionally, its own member nations were divided.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, trying to recover market share, increased production, pushing prices down, shrinking or eliminating profits for high-cost producers.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The world price, which had peaked during the 1979 energy crisis at nearly $40 per barrel, decreased during the 1980s to less than $10 per barrel.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Adjusted for inflation, oil briefly fell back to pre-1973 levels.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This "sale" price was a windfall for oil-importing nations, both developing and developed.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the Iran–Iraq War of 1980–1988, the stated war aim of Iran was to overthrow the Baath regime in Iraq.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, Saudi Arabia and the other Arab Gulf states leaned in a very pro-Iraqi neutrality during the war.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a part of its policy of supporting Iraq, Saudi Arabia pumped out oil in massive quantities to lower the price as a way of hurting Iran's economy.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The low price of oil also hurt Iraq's economy, which forced Iraq to borrow massive sums of money, putting Iraq deeply into debt.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In contrast, Iran refused to borrow any money because of its refusal to pay interest on any loans, and paid the costs of the war directly from the sale of its oil.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Iran's revenue from the sale of oil went from $20 billion US dollars per year in 1982 to $5 billion US dollars per year by 1988, which pushed Iran to the verge of bankruptcy and forced Iran to make peace with Iraq later in 1988.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the war, the Iranian delegation at OPEC tried very hard to have the group cut production to raise prices, but were blocked by the other delegations led by the Saudi delegation, who insisted on more oil production.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The embargo encouraged new venues for energy exploration, including Alaska, the North Sea, the Caspian Sea, and the Caucasus.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Exploration in the Caspian Basin and Siberia became profitable.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Cooperation changed into a far more adversarial relationship as the USSR increased its production.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, the Soviet Union had become the world's largest producer.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Part of the decline in prices and economic and geopolitical power of OPEC came from the move to alternative energy sources.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC had relied on price inelasticity to maintain high consumption, but had underestimated the extent to which conservation and other sources of supply would eventually reduce demand.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Electricity generation from nuclear power and natural gas, home heating from natural gas, and ethanol-blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The drop in prices presented a serious problem for oil-exporting countries in northern Europe and the Persian Gulf.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Heavily populated, impoverished countries, whose economies were largely dependent on oil—including Mexico, Nigeria, Algeria, and Libya—did not prepare for a market reversal that left them in sometimes desperate situations.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When reduced demand and increased production glutted the world market in the mid-1980s, oil prices plummeted and the cartel lost its unity.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mexico (a non-member), Nigeria, and Venezuela, whose economies had expanded in the 1970s, faced near-bankruptcy, and even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The divisions within OPEC made concerted action more difficult.
[src:propfan/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As of 2015, OPEC has never approached its earlier dominance.
[src:propfan/2003-in-aviation] This is a list of aviation-related events from 2003.
[src:propfan/2003-in-aviation] Etihad Airways was formed and the first flight was to Al Ain and Beirut.
[src:propfan/2003-in-aviation] The deadliest crash of this year was a military accident, namely the 2003 Iran Ilyushin Il-76 crash, which crashed in mountainous terrain of southeastern Iran on 19 February, killing all 275 people on board.
[src:propfan/2003-in-aviation] The deadliest civil aviation crash was UTAGE Flight 141, a Boeing 727 which crashed on takeoff in Cotonou, Benin on 25 December, killing 141 of the 160 people on board.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:propfan/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Hearing is one of the most crucial means of survival in the animal world and speech is one of the most distinctive characteristics of human development and culture.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Accordingly, the science of acoustics spreads across many facets of human society—music, medicine, architecture, industrial production, warfare and more.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Likewise, animal species such as songbirds and frogs use sound and hearing as a key element of mating rituals or for marking territories.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Art, craft, science and technology have provoked one another to advance the whole, as in many other fields of knowledge.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Robert Bruce Lindsay's "Wheel of Acoustics" is a well-accepted overview of the various fields in acoustics.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The word "acoustic" is derived from the ἀκουστικός (*akoustikós*), meaning "of or for hearing" and "ready to hear", and from ἀκουστός (*akoustós*), "heard, audible", which in turn derives from the verb ἀκούω (*akoúō*), "to hear".
[src:propfan/acoustics] The Latin synonym is "sonic", after which the term **sonics** used to be a synonym for acoustics and later a branch of acoustics.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Frequencies above and below the audible range are called "ultrasonic" and "infrasonic", respectively.
[src:propfan/acoustics] In the 6th century BCE, the ancient Greek philosopher Pythagoras wanted to know why some combinations of musical sounds seemed more beautiful than others, and he found answers in terms of numerical ratios representing the harmonic overtone series on a string.
[src:propfan/acoustics] He is reputed to have observed that when the lengths of vibrating strings are expressible as ratios of integers (e.g.
[src:propfan/acoustics] 2 to 3, 3 to 4), the tones produced will be harmonious, and the smaller the integers the more harmonious the sounds.
[src:propfan/acoustics] For example, a string of a certain length would sound particularly harmonious with a string of twice the length (other factors being equal).
[src:propfan/acoustics] In modern parlance, if a string sounds the note C when plucked, a string twice as long will sound a C an octave lower.
[src:propfan/acoustics] In one system of musical tuning, the tones in between are then given by 16:9 for D, 8:5 for E, 3:2 for F, 4:3 for G, 6:5 for A, and 16:15 for B, in ascending order.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Aristotle (384–322 BCE) understood that sound consisted of compressions and rarefactions of air which "falls upon and strikes the air which is next to it...", a very good expression of the nature of wave motion.
[src:propfan/acoustics] *On Things Heard*, generally ascribed to Strato of Lampsacus, states that the pitch is related to the frequency of vibrations of the air and to the speed of sound.
[src:propfan/acoustics] In about 20 BCE, the Roman architect and engineer Vitruvius wrote a treatise on the acoustic properties of theaters, including a discussion of interference, echoes, and reverberation—the beginnings of architectural acoustics.
[src:propfan/acoustics] In Book V of his *De architectura* (*The Ten Books of Architecture*) Vitruvius described sound as a wave comparable to a water wave extended to three dimensions, which, when interrupted by obstructions, would flow back and break up following waves.
[src:propfan/acoustics] During the Islamic golden age, Abū Rayhān al-Bīrūnī (973–1048) is believed to have postulated that the speed of sound was much slower than the speed of light.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The physical understanding of acoustical processes advanced rapidly during and after the Scientific Revolution.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Mainly Galileo Galilei (1564–1642) but also Marin Mersenne (1588–1648), independently, discovered the complete laws of vibrating strings (completing what Pythagoras and Pythagoreans had started 2000 years earlier).
[src:propfan/acoustics] Galileo wrote "Waves are produced by the vibrations of a sonorous body, which spread through the air, bringing to the tympanum of the ear a stimulus which the mind interprets as sound", a remarkable statement that points to the beginnings of physiological and psychological acoustics.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Experimental measurements of the speed of sound in air were carried out successfully between 1630 and 1680 by a number of investigators, prominently Mersenne.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Inspired by Mersenne's *Harmonie universelle* (*Universal Harmony*) of 1634, the Rome-based Jesuit scholar Athanasius Kircher undertook research in acoustics.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Kircher published two major books on acoustics: the *Musurgia universalis* (*Universal Music-Making*) in 1650 and the *Phonurgia nova* (*New Sound-Making*) in 1673.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Meanwhile, Newton (1642–1727) derived the relationship for wave velocity in solids, a cornerstone of physical acoustics (Principia, 1687).
[src:propfan/acoustics] Substantial progress in acoustics, resting on firmer mathematical and physical concepts, was made during the eighteenth century by Euler (1707–1783), Lagrange (1736–1813), and d'Alembert (1717–1783).
[src:propfan/acoustics] During this era, continuum physics, or field theory, began to receive a definite mathematical structure.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The wave equation emerged in a number of contexts, including the propagation of sound in air.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Also in the 19th century, Wheatstone, Ohm, and Henry developed the analogy between electricity and acoustics.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The twentieth century saw a burgeoning of technological applications of the large body of scientific knowledge that was by then in place.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The first such application was Sabine's groundbreaking work in architectural acoustics, and many others followed.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Underwater acoustics was used for detecting submarines in the First World War.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Sound recording and the telephone played important roles in a global transformation of society.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Sound measurement and analysis reached new levels of accuracy and sophistication through the use of electronics and computing.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The ultrasonic frequency range enabled wholly new kinds of application in medicine and industry.
[src:propfan/acoustics] New kinds of transducers (generators and receivers of acoustic energy) were invented and put to use.
[src:propfan/acoustics] , both suspended on an overhead steel trellis, to synthesize an indoor acoustic environment outdoors.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Acoustics is defined by ANSI/ASA S1.1-2013 as "(a) Science of sound, including its production, transmission, and effects, including biological and psychological effects.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The study of acoustics revolves around the generation, propagation and reception of mechanical waves and vibrations.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The steps shown in the above diagram can be found in any acoustical event or process.
[src:propfan/acoustics] There are many kinds of causes, both natural and volitional.
[src:propfan/acoustics] There are many kinds of transduction processes that convert energy from some other form into sonic energy, producing a sound wave.
[src:propfan/acoustics] There is one fundamental equation that describes sound wave propagation, the acoustic wave equation, but the phenomena that emerge from it are varied and often complex.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The wave carries energy throughout the propagating medium.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Eventually this energy is transduced again into other forms, in ways that again may be natural and/or volitionally contrived.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The final effect may be purely physical or it may reach far into the biological or volitional domains.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The five basic steps are found equally well whether we are talking about an earthquake, a submarine using sonar to locate its foe, or a band playing in a rock concert.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The central stage in the acoustical process is wave propagation.
[src:propfan/acoustics] This falls within the domain of physical acoustics.
[src:propfan/acoustics] In fluids, sound propagates primarily as a pressure wave.
[src:propfan/acoustics] In solids, mechanical waves can take many forms including longitudinal waves, transverse waves and surface waves.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Acoustics looks first at the pressure levels and frequencies in the sound wave and how the wave interacts with the environment.
[src:propfan/acoustics] This interaction can be described as either a diffraction, interference or a reflection or a mix of the three.
[src:propfan/acoustics] If several media are present, a refraction can also occur.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Transduction processes are also of special importance to acoustics.
[src:propfan/acoustics] In fluids such as air and water, sound waves propagate as disturbances in the ambient pressure level.
[src:propfan/acoustics] While this disturbance is usually small, it is still noticeable to the human ear.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The smallest sound that a person can hear, known as the threshold of hearing, is nine orders of magnitude smaller than the ambient pressure.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The loudness of these disturbances is related to the sound pressure level (SPL), which is measured on a logarithmic scale in decibels.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Physicists and acoustic engineers tend to discuss sound pressure levels in terms of frequencies, partly because this is how our ears interpret sound.
[src:propfan/acoustics] What we experience as "higher pitched" or "lower pitched" sounds are pressure vibrations having a higher or lower number of cycles per second.
[src:propfan/acoustics] In a common technique of acoustic measurement, acoustic signals are sampled in time, and then presented in more meaningful forms such as octave bands or time frequency plots.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Both of these popular methods are used to analyze sound and better understand the acoustic phenomenon.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The entire spectrum can be divided into three sections: audio, ultrasonic, and infrasonic.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The audio range falls between 20 Hz and 20,000 Hz.
[src:propfan/acoustics] This range is important because its frequencies can be detected by the human ear.
[src:propfan/acoustics] This range has a number of applications, including speech communication and music.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The ultrasonic range refers to the very high frequencies: 20,000 Hz and higher.
[src:propfan/acoustics] This range has shorter wavelengths which allow better resolution in imaging technologies.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Medical applications such as ultrasonography and elastography rely on the ultrasonic frequency range.
[src:propfan/acoustics] On the other end of the spectrum, the lowest frequencies are known as the infrasonic range.
[src:propfan/acoustics] These frequencies can be used to study geological phenomena such as earthquakes.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Analytic instruments such as the spectrum analyzer facilitate visualization and measurement of acoustic signals and their properties.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The spectrogram produced by such an instrument is a graphical display of the time varying pressure level and frequency profiles that give a specific acoustic signal its defining character.
[src:propfan/acoustics] A transducer is a device for converting one form of energy into another.
[src:propfan/acoustics] In an electroacoustic context, this means converting sound energy into electrical energy (or vice versa).
[src:propfan/acoustics] Electroacoustic transducers include loudspeakers, microphones, particle velocity sensors, hydrophones and sonar projectors.
[src:propfan/acoustics] These devices convert a sound wave to or from an electric signal.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The most widely used transduction principles are electromagnetism, electrostatics and piezoelectricity.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The transducers in most common loudspeakers (e.g. woofers and tweeters), are electromagnetic devices that generate waves using a suspended diaphragm driven by an electromagnetic voice coil, sending off pressure waves.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Electret microphones and condenser microphones employ electrostatics—as the sound wave strikes the microphone's diaphragm, it moves and induces a voltage change.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The ultrasonic systems used in medical ultrasonography employ piezoelectric transducers.
[src:propfan/acoustics] These are made from special ceramics in which mechanical vibrations and electrical fields are interlinked through a property of the material itself.
[src:propfan/acoustics] An acoustician is an expert in the science of sound.
[src:propfan/acoustics] There are many types of acousticians, but they usually have a Bachelor's degree or higher qualification.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Some possess a degree in acoustics, while others enter the discipline via studies in fields such as physics or engineering.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Much work in acoustics requires a good grounding in mathematics and science.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Many acoustic scientists work in research and development.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Some conduct basic research to advance our knowledge of the perception (e.g. hearing, psychoacoustics or neurophysiology) of speech, music and noise.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Other acoustic scientists advance understanding of how sound is affected as it moves through environments, e.g. underwater acoustics, architectural acoustics or structural acoustics.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Other areas of work are listed under subdisciplines below.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Acoustic scientists work in government, university and private industry laboratories.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Many go on to work in acoustical engineering.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Some positions, such as faculty (academic staff) require a Doctor of Philosophy.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Archaeoacoustics, also known as the archaeology of sound, is one of the only ways to experience the past with senses other than our eyes.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Archaeoacoustics is studied by testing the acoustic properties of prehistoric sites, including caves.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Iegor Rezkinoff, a sound archaeologist, studies the acoustic properties of caves through natural sounds like humming and whistling.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Archaeological theories of acoustics are focused around ritualistic purposes as well as a way of echolocation in the caves.
[src:propfan/acoustics] In archaeology, acoustic sounds and rituals directly correlate as specific sounds were meant to bring ritual participants closer to a spiritual awakening.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Parallels can also be drawn between cave wall paintings and the acoustic properties of the cave; they are both dynamic.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Because archaeoacoustics is a fairly new archaeological subject, acoustic sound is still being tested in these prehistoric sites today.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Aeroacoustics is the study of noise generated by air movement, for instance via turbulence, and the movement of sound through the fluid air.
[src:propfan/acoustics] This knowledge was applied in the 1920s and '30s to detect aircraft before radar was invented and is applied in acoustical engineering to study how to quieten aircraft.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Aeroacoustics is important for understanding how wind musical instruments work.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Acoustic signal processing is the electronic manipulation of acoustic signals.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Applications include: active noise control; design for hearing aids or cochlear implants; echo cancellation; music information retrieval, and perceptual coding (e.g.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Architectural acoustics (also known as building acoustics) involves the scientific understanding of how to achieve good sound within a building.
[src:propfan/acoustics] It typically involves the study of speech intelligibility, speech privacy, music quality, and vibration reduction in the built environment.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Commonly studied environments are hospitals, classrooms, dwellings, performance venues, recording and broadcasting studios.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Focus considerations include room acoustics, airborne and impact transmission in building structures, airborne and structure-borne noise control, noise control of building systems and electroacoustic systems.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Bioacoustics is the scientific study of the hearing and calls of animals, as well as how animals are affected by the acoustic and sounds of their habitat.
[src:propfan/acoustics] This subdiscipline is concerned with the recording, manipulation and reproduction of audio using electronics.
[src:propfan/acoustics] This might include products such as mobile phones, large scale public address systems or virtual reality systems in research laboratories.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Environmental acoustics is the study of noise and vibrations, and their impact on structures, objects, humans, and animals.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The main aim of these studies is to reduce levels of environmental noise and vibration.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Typical work and research within environmental acoustics concerns the development of models used in simulations, measurement techniques, noise mitigation strategies, and the development of standards and regulations.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Research work now also has a focus on the positive use of sound in urban environments: soundscapes and tranquility.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Examples of noise and vibration sources include railways, road traffic, aircraft, industrial equipment and recreational activities.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Musical acoustics is the study of the physics of acoustic instruments; the audio signal processing used in electronic music; the computer analysis of music and composition, and the perception and cognitive neuroscience of music.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Many studies have been conducted to identify the relationship between acoustics and cognition, or more commonly known as psychoacoustics, in which what one hears is a combination of perception and biological aspects.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The information intercepted by the passage of sound waves through the ear is understood and interpreted through the brain, emphasizing the connection between the mind and acoustics.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Psychological changes have been seen as brain waves slow down or speed up as a result of varying auditory stimulus which can in turn affect the way one thinks, feels, or even behaves.
[src:propfan/acoustics] This correlation can be viewed in normal, everyday situations in which listening to an upbeat or uptempo song can cause one's foot to start tapping or a slower song can leave one feeling calm and serene.
[src:propfan/acoustics] In a deeper biological look at the phenomenon of psychoacoustics, it was discovered that the central nervous system is activated by basic acoustical characteristics of music.
[src:propfan/acoustics] By observing how the central nervous system, which includes the brain and spine, is influenced by acoustics, the pathway in which acoustics affects the mind, and essentially the body, is evident.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Acousticians study the production, processing and perception of speech.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Speech recognition and speech synthesis are two important areas of speech processing using computers.
[src:propfan/acoustics] The subject also overlaps with the disciplines of physics, physiology, psychology, and linguistics.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Structural acoustics is the study of motions and interactions of mechanical systems with their environments and the methods of their measurement, analysis, and control.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Ultrasonics deals with sounds at frequencies too high to be heard by humans.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Specialisms include medical ultrasonics (including medical ultrasonography), ultrasonic sensors, sonochemistry, ultrasonic testing, material characterisation and underwater acoustics (sonar).
[src:propfan/acoustics] Underwater acoustics is the scientific study of natural and man-made sounds underwater.
[src:propfan/acoustics] Applications include sonar to locate submarines, underwater communication by whales, climate change monitoring by measuring sea temperatures acoustically, sonic weapons, and marine bioacoustics.
[src:propfan/ainonline] The Convention News Company was founded by aviation editor James Holahan and publisher Wilson S.
[src:propfan/ainonline] Leach in 1972 and published its first issues at that year's NBAA convention.
[src:propfan/ainonline] Now branded as AIN Media Group, it has branched into other aviation sectors and other products, and still publishes NBAA Convention News.
[src:propfan/ainonline] In 2002, Aviation International News received an award for "excellent, accurate and insightful reporting of issues related to the business aviation industry" from the National Business Aviation Association at its 55th Annual Meeting & Convention.
[src:propfan/ainonline] It interviews prominent travelers, including Sir Richard Branson, Suze Orman, Wolfgang Puck, T.
[src:propfan/ainonline] Boone Pickens, Rudy Giuliani, Mark Cuban, Donald Trump, Arnold Palmer, James Carville, Buzz Aldrin, William Shatner, Morgan Freeman, Herbie Hancock, and many other celebrities.
[src:propfan/ainonline] Annual features include results of a Readers' Choice Poll.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Leonardo's manufacturing facilities in Pomigliano d'Arco, near Naples, Italy, produce the aircraft's fuselage and tail sections.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Aircraft wings are assembled at Sogerma in Bordeaux in western France by Airbus France.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Final assembly, flight-testing, certification and deliveries are the responsibility of ATR in Toulouse, France.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During the 1960s and 1970s, European aircraft manufacturers had, for the most part, undergone considerable corporate restructuring, including mergers and consolidations, as well as moved towards collaborative multi-national programmes, such as the newly launched Airbus A300.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In line with this trend towards intra-European cooperation, French aerospace company Aérospatiale and Italian aviation conglomerate Aeritalia commenced discussions on the topic of working together to develop an all-new regional airliner.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Prior to this, both companies had been independently conducting studies for their own aircraft concepts, the *AS 35* design in the case of Aerospatiale and the *AIT 230* for Aeritalia, to conform with demand within this sector of the market as early as 1978.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 4 November 1981, a formal Cooperation Agreement was signed by Aeritalia chairman Renato Bonifacio and Aérospatiale chairman Jacques Mitterrand in Paris, France.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] This agreement signaled not only the merger of their efforts but of their separate concept designs together into a single complete aircraft design for the purpose of pursuing its development and manufacture as a collaborative joint venture.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The consortium targeted a similar unit cost but a 950 lb (430 kg) fuel consumption over a 200 nmi (370 km) sector, nearly half the 1,750 lb (790 kg) required by its 40-50 seat competitors, the British Aerospace HS.748 and Fokker F.27, and planned a 58-seat ATR XX stretch.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] This agreement served not only as the basis and origins of the ATR company, but also as the effective launch point of what would become the fledgling firm's first aircraft, which was designated as the *ATR 42*.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] By 1983, ATR's customer services division has been set up, readying infrastructure worldwide to provide support for ATR's upcoming aircraft to any customer regardless of location.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 16 August 1984, the first model of the type, known as the *ATR 42–200*, conducted its maiden flight from Toulouse Airport, France.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During September 1985, both the French Directorate General for Civil Aviation (DGCA) and the Italian Italian Civil Aviation Authority awarded type certification for the type, clearing it to commence operational service.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 3 December 1985, the first production aircraft, designated as the *ATR 42-300*, was delivered to French launch customer Air Littoral; the first revenue service was performed later that same month.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During January 1986, already confident of the ATR 42's success and of the demand for an enlarged version of the aircraft, ATR announced that the launch of a programme to develop such an aircraft, which was designated as the ATR 72 to reflect its increased passenger capacity.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During 1988, the 200th ATR was delivered to Thai Airways.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During September 1989, it was announced that ATR had achieved its original target of 400 sales of the ATR.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] That same year, deliveries of the enlarged ATR 72 commenced; shortly thereafter, it became common for both types to be ordered together.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Since the smaller ATR 42 is assembled on the same production line as the ATR 72, along with sharing the majority of subsystems, components, and manufacturing techniques, the two types support each other to remain in production.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] This factor may have been crucial as, by 2015, the ATR 42 was the only 50-seat regional aircraft that was still being manufactured.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During September 1992, the 300th ATR was delivered to Finnish airline Karair.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The 500th ATR was delivered to American Eagle, USA, on 5 September 1997.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In order to maintain a technological edge on the highly competitive market for regional airliners during the 1990s, several modifications and improved versions of the ATR 42 were progressively introduced.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The initial ATR 42-300 model remained in production until 1996, while the first upgraded (and broadly similar) model, designated as the *ATR 42-320*, was also produced until 1996.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The -320 variant principally differed in that it was powered by a pair of the more-powerful PW121 engines, giving it improved performance over the 300.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Another variant, the *ATR 42-300QC*, was a dedicated 'quick-change' (convertible) freight/passenger version of the standard −300 series.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The next major production version was the *ATR 42−500* series, the development of which was originally announced on 14 June 1993.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 31 October 1995, the first ATR 42-500 was delivered to Italian operator Air Dolomiti; on 19 January 1996, the first revenue service to be performed by the type was conducted.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In addition to new aircraft models, various organisational changes were also implemented.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 10 July 1998, ATR launched its new Asset Management Department.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 28 April 2000, the 600th ATR, an ATR 72-500, was delivered to Italian operator Air Dolomiti.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The 700th aircraft, an ATR 72-500, was delivered to Indian airline Simplify Deccan, on 8 September 2006.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In June 2001, EADS and Alenia Aeronautica, ATR's parent companies, decided to reinforce their partnership, regrouping all industrial activities related to regional airliners underneath the ATR consortium.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 3 October 2003, ATR became one of the first aircraft manufacturers to be certified under ISO 9001-2000 and EN/AS/JISQ 9100, the worldwide quality standard for the aeronautics industry.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During July 2004, ATR and Brazilian aircraft manufacturer Embraer announced a cooperation agreement on the AEROChain Portal for the purpose of delivering improved customer service.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During April 2009, ATR announces the launch of its 'Door-2-Door' service as a new option in its comprehensive customer services range.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 2 October 2007, ATR CEO Stéphane Mayer announced the launch of the −600 series aircraft; the ATR 42–600 and ATR 72–600 featured various improvements to increase efficiency, dispatch reliability, lower fuel burn and operating costs.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] While broadly similar to the earlier -500 model, differences include the adoption of improved PW127M engines, a new glass cockpit, and a variety of other minor improvements.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Using the test registration *F-WWLY*, the prototype ATR 42–600 first flew on 4 March 2010.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The 900th aircraft, an ATR 72-500, was delivered to Brazilian airline TRIP Linhas Aéreas on 10 September 2010.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During 2011, Royal Air Maroc took delivery of the first ATR 72-600.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The 1,000th aircraft was delivered to Spain's Air Nostrum on May 3, 2012.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 15 June 2015, Japan Air Commuter signed a contract for ATR's 1,500th aircraft.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 1 February 2016, ATR signed a major agreement with Iran Air for 40 ATR 72-600s.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The 1,300th ATR, an ATR 72-600, was delivered to NAC for operation by Irish airline Stobart Air on 14 June 2016; that same year, ATR delivered the first ever ATR 72-600 High Capacity aircraft (78 seats) to Cebu Pacific.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In October 2016, Christian Scherer was appointed CEO.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In 2017, ATR celebrated its 35th anniversary.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 1 February, ATR and Sweden's BRA performed the first ATR biofuel flight.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During August 2017, US regional carrier Silver Airways signed a letter of intent for up to 50 ATR 42, a return to the continental US market since 1997 when American Airlines converted 12 ATR 72 options, due to the rise of regional jets and the American Eagle Flight 4184 crash in 1994.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] ATR lowered its output to 80 deliveries a year from 2017 and boasts a nearly three-year backlog after FedEx Express' November 2017 order.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In 2017, ATR booked 113 firm orders and 40 options, and delivered 80 aircraft: 70 new ATR 72-600s, 8 new ATR 42-600s and 2 second hand ATRs.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] By April 2018, the fleet was flying more than 5,000 times per day and had operated 30 million flight hours.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] By the end of June 2018, Leonardo had shipped the 1,500th ATR fuselage while nearly 1,700 airliners had been ordered; ATR reportedly led the turboprop regional airliner market since 2010 with a 75% share.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The company's aircraft were being operated in nearly 100 countries by 200 airlines and 30 million flights had been completed; it was also claimed that an ATR airliner takes off or lands every 8 seconds.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 13 September, Scherer left its CEO role to replace Eric Schulz as Airbus' Chief Commercial Officer.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] ATR replaced Scherer as its chief executive with Stefano Bortoli, president of ATR's board and Leonardo aircraft's senior vice-president for strategy and marketing.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] At the end of October, the 1,500th ATR was delivered, an ATR 72-600 to Japan Air Commuter, after nearly 500 ATR 42s and more than 1,000 ATR 72s deliveries to over 200 operators in 100 countries.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During 2018, ATR delivered 76 aircraft; the rate of production has held at a stable rate.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The company opted to pursue a low-risk strategy, avoiding disruptive measures while opting to integrate relatively straightforward enhancements onto its aircraft, such as the Elbit Systems ClearVision wearable enhanced vision system.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In May 2022, ATR started studying an *Evo* hybrid-electric variant, aiming for a 2023 launch and service entry before 2030.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] An optimized turboprop running on SAF would be supplemented by a mild hybridization during the take-off and climb phases for a 20% lower fuel burn.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Other improvements could include an eight-bladed propeller, thermal de-icing to replace the current pneumatic boots, a single lever FADEC for both engine and propeller and an aerodynamic clean-up of the secondary structures like the nacelle-wing junction.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] A cabin revamp would save weight with recycled carbonfibre or bio-sourced resin and natural fibres.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On September 17, 2022, Stefano Bortoli was succeeded as CEO of ATR by Nathalie Tarnaud Laude, former president of NHIndustries and Senior Vice President Head of the NH90 Programme for Airbus Helicopters.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 21 June 2022, ATR completed its first flight as a 100% SAF-powered regional aircraft.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On November 13, 2024, ATR declared that it would scrap its development of a new model designed to take off and land on short runways and instead concentrate instead on its existing portfolio.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] This project was undertaken in 2019, where it announced its plans to develop a unique version of its smallest model to squeeze in and out of airports with runways as short as 800 metres (2,600 feet).
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 26 March 2026, reports indicated that Airbus is in talks with stakeholders to establish a Final Assembly Line (FAL) for the ATR regional aircraft in India.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The aerospace major is evaluating a feasibility for a business case.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] was a military variant of the ATR 72-100 that included a rear ramp-type cargo door and strengthened cabin floor.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Beginning in the mid-1980s, the company investigated an 86-seat derivative of the ATR 72.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] for aircraft that seated fewer than 90 passengers.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The aircraft would have a cruising speed as high as 330 knots (610 km/h; 380 mph).
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] proposal, ATR floated the idea of a 90–99 seater stretch.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] As of 2009, it was considered part of the future -900 series ATR family.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In 2011, the 90-seater was proposed to shareholders.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] As of 2012, a new clean-sheet design was considered in the 90-seat segment, for a 2017 launch.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] As of 2017, development of a 90-seater for an expected demand of 2,000–2,500 units over 20 years was expected to cost more than $5bn.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Fuel burn would need to be reduced by at least 30%, and the unit price would need to stay in the low-to-mid-$20m range, below small jets.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Leonardo preferred a clean-sheet 90-100 seater with new turboprops, wings and cockpit available soon but Airbus favoured a medium-term introduction with disruptive hybrid electric engines, structural advanced materials and automation.
[src:propfan/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In January 2018, Leonardo abandoned the 100-seater prospect, favouring existing ATR 42 and 72 models which dominate the turboprop market with a 75% share.
[src:propfan/atra-90] The **Advanced Technology Regional Aircraft 90** (**ATRA-90**) was a propfan-powered regional aircraft that was proposed in 1986.
[src:propfan/atra-90] Conceived by Industri Pesawat Terbang Nusantara (IPTN) of Indonesia, the multi-national project was also backed by Boeing of the United States, Fokker of the Netherlands, and Messerschmitt-Bölkow-Blohm (MBB) of West Germany.
[src:propfan/atra-90] The ATRA-90 was targeted for introduction between 1992 and 1995, but the project was put on hold in 1988.
[src:propfan/atra-90] The aircraft was designed to transport between 83 and 115 passengers a distance of 1,500–2,100 nautical miles (2,800–3,900 kilometers; 1,700–2,400 miles).
[src:propfan/atra-90] It would cruise at a speed of Mach 0.8 and an altitude of 9,100 meters (30,000 feet).
[src:propfan/propfan] A **propfan**, also called a **propjet**, an **open rotor engine**, or an **open fan engine**, is an aircraft engine combining features of turbofans and turboprops.
[src:propfan/propfan] It uses advanced, curved propeller blades without a duct.
[src:propfan/propfan] Propfans first started prototype testing in the 1970s, aiming to combine the speed capability of turbofans with the fuel efficiency of turboprops, especially at high subsonic speeds.
[src:propfan/propfan] However, they have never proceeded beyond testing, never going into commercial use.
[src:propfan/propfan] Over the decades, different efforts to perfect the concept have used names like "open rotor" and "ultra-high-bypass (UHB) turbofan".
[src:propfan/propfan] In 1986, British engine maker Rolls-Royce used the term *open rotor* as a synonym for the original meaning of a propfan.
[src:propfan/propfan] This action was to delineate the propfan engine type from a number of ducted engine proposals at the time that had *propfan* in their names.
[src:propfan/propfan] By the 2000s, *open rotor* (OR) became a preferred term for propfan technology in research and news reports, with *contra-rotating open rotor* (CROR) also occasionally being used to distinguish between single-rotation propfans.
[src:propfan/propfan] About a decade after German aerospace engineers began exploring the idea of using swept wings to reduce drag on transonic speed aircraft, Hamilton Standard in the 1940s attempted to apply a similar concept to aircraft propellers.
[src:propfan/propfan] It created highly swept propeller blades with supersonic tip speeds, so that engines with exposed propellers could power aircraft to speeds and cruising altitudes only attained by new turbojet and turbofan engines.
[src:propfan/propfan] Early tests of these blades revealed then-unresolvable blade flutter and blade stress problems, and high noise levels were considered another obstacle.
[src:propfan/propfan] The popularity of turbojets and turbofans curtailed research in propellers, but by the 1960s, interest increased when studies showed that an exposed propeller driven by a gas turbine could power an airliner flying at a speed of Mach 0.7–0.8 and at an altitude of 35,000 feet (11,000 metres).
[src:propfan/propfan] The term propfan was created during this period.
[src:propfan/propfan] One of the earliest engines that resembled the propfan concept was the 4,710 pounds-force (21.0 kilonewtons) Metrovick F.5, which featured twin contra-rotating fans—14 blades in the fore (front) fan and 12 blades in the aft (back) fan—at the rear of the engine and was first run in 1946.
[src:propfan/propfan] The blades, however, were mostly unswept.
[src:propfan/propfan] Both setups had four largely unswept blades in the front propeller and the back propeller.
[src:propfan/propfan] When the 1973 oil crisis caused petroleum price spikes in the early 1970s, interest in propfans soared, and NASA-funded research began to accelerate.
[src:propfan/propfan] The propfan concept was outlined by Carl Rohrbach and Bruce Metzger of the Hamilton Standard division of United Technologies in 1975 and was patented by Rohrbach and Robert Cornell of Hamilton Standard in 1979.
[src:propfan/propfan] Later work by General Electric on similar propulsors adopted the name unducted fan, which was a modified turbofan engine, with the fan placed outside the engine nacelle on the same axis as the compressor blades.
[src:propfan/propfan] During this era, the propeller problems became fixable.
[src:propfan/propfan] Advances were made in structural materials, such as titanium metal and graphite and glass fiber composites infused with resin.
[src:propfan/propfan] These materials replaced aluminum and steel metals in blade construction, which allowed the blades to be made thinner and stronger.
[src:propfan/propfan] Computer-aided design was also useful in refining blade characteristics.
[src:propfan/propfan] Since the blades bend and deflect with higher power loading and centrifugal force, the initial designs needed to be based on the in-motion shape.
[src:propfan/propfan] With the help of computers, the blade designers would then work backward to find the optimal unloaded shape for manufacturing purposes.
[src:propfan/propfan] Hamilton Standard, the only large American manufacturer of aircraft propellers, developed the propfan concept in the early 1970s.
[src:propfan/propfan] Hamilton Standard tested numerous variations in conjunction with NASA.
[src:propfan/propfan] Under the Propfan Test Assessment (PTA) program, Lockheed-Georgia proposed modifying a Gulfstream II to act as in-flight testbed for the propfan concept, while McDonnell Douglas proposed modifying a DC-9 for the same purpose.
[src:propfan/propfan] The Gulfstream II had a nacelle added to the left wing, containing a 6,000 horsepower (4,500 kilowatts) Allison 570 turboprop engine (derived from the XT701 turboshaft developed for the Boeing Vertol XCH-62 heavy lift helicopter).
[src:propfan/propfan] The engine used an eight-bladed, 9-foot diameter (2.7-metre; 110-inch; 270-centimetre), single-rotation Hamilton Standard SR-7 propfan.
[src:propfan/propfan] The test engine, which was named the Allison 501-M78, had a thrust rating of 9,000 lbf (40 kN).
[src:propfan/propfan] It was first operated in flight on March 28, 1987.
[src:propfan/propfan] The extensive test program, which cost about $56 million, racked up 73 flights and over 133 hours of flight time before finishing on March 25, 1988.
[src:propfan/propfan] In 1989, however, the testbed aircraft returned to the air from April 3 through April 14 to measure ground noise levels during flight.
[src:propfan/propfan] The engine was removed after that, and the aircraft was converted to a space shuttle training aircraft later that year.
[src:propfan/propfan] The GE36 Unducted Fan (UDF), from American engine maker General Electric (GE) with 35-percent participation from French partner Snecma (now Safran), was a variation on the original propfan concept and resembled a pusher configuration piston engine.
[src:propfan/propfan] GE's UDF had a novel direct-drive arrangement, where the reduction gearbox was replaced by a low-speed seven-stage free turbine.
[src:propfan/propfan] One set of turbine rotors drove the forward set of propellers, while the rear set was driven by the other set of rotors which rotated in the opposite direction.
[src:propfan/propfan] The turbine had 14 blade rows with seven stages.
[src:propfan/propfan] Each stage was a pair of contra-rotating rows.
[src:propfan/propfan] The GE36 was first flight tested mounted on the #3 engine station of a Boeing 727-100 on August 20, 1986.
[src:propfan/propfan] They replaced the left side JT8D turbofan engine with the GE36.
[src:propfan/propfan] Test flights began in May 1987, which proved the design's airworthiness, aerodynamic characteristics, and noise signature.
[src:propfan/propfan] Following the initial tests, a first-class cabin was installed inside the aft fuselage and airline executives were offered the opportunity to experience the UDF-powered aircraft first-hand.
[src:propfan/propfan] The test and marketing flights of the GE-outfitted demonstrator aircraft concluded in 1988, exhibiting a 30% reduction in fuel consumption over turbo-fan powered MD-80, full Stage 3 noise compliance, and low levels of interior noise/vibration.
[src:propfan/propfan] The GE36 would have the same 25,000 lbf (110 kN) thrust on the MD-92X, but the same engine would be derated to 22,000 lbf (98 kN) thrust for the smaller MD-91X.
[src:propfan/propfan] The MD-80 was also successfully flight tested in April 1989 with the 578-DX propfan, which was a prototype from the Allison Engine Company (at that time a division of General Motors) that was also derived from the Allison XT701 and built with Hamilton Standard propellers.
[src:propfan/propfan] The engine program was jointly developed between Allison and another division of United Technologies, the engine maker Pratt & Whitney.
[src:propfan/propfan] Unlike the competing GE36 UDF, the 578-DX was fairly conventional, having a reduction gearbox between the LP turbine and the propfan blades.
[src:propfan/propfan] Due to jet fuel price drops and shifting marketing priorities, Douglas shelved the propfan program later that year.
[src:propfan/propfan] None of these projects came to fruition, however, mainly because of excessive cabin noise (compared to turbofans) and low fuel prices.
[src:propfan/propfan] For General Electric, the GE36 UDF was meant to replace the CFM56 high-bypass turbofan that it produced with equal partner Snecma in their CFM International joint venture.
[src:propfan/propfan] In the 1980s the engine was initially uncompetitive against the International Aero Engines rival offering, the IAE V2500.
[src:propfan/propfan] In December 1986, the chairman of Snecma declared that the in-development CFM56-5S2 would be the last turbofan created for the CFM56 family, and that *"*There is no point in spending more money on turbofans.
[src:propfan/propfan] UDF is the future." The V2500 ran into technical problems in 1987, however, and the CFM56 gained major sales momentum.
[src:propfan/propfan] At the beginning of the 1990s, the Soviet Union/Russia performed flight tests on the Progress D-236, a geared contra-rotating propfan engine based on the core of the Progress D-36 turbofan, with eight blades on the front propeller and six blades on the back propeller.
[src:propfan/propfan] One testbed was a 10,100 hp (7,500 kW) propfan mounted to an Ilyushin Il-76 and flown to the Hannover ILA 90 airshow, which was intended for an unidentified four-propfan aircraft.
[src:propfan/propfan] The D-236 flew 36 times for a total of 70 flight test hours on the Il-76.
[src:propfan/propfan] The Soviets claimed the D-236 had a true aerodynamic efficiency of 28 percent and a fuel savings of 30 percent over an equivalent turboprop.
[src:propfan/propfan] They also revealed plans for propfans with power ratings of 14,100 and 30,200 hp (10,500 and 22,500 kW).
[src:propfan/propfan] Like the Progress D-236, the more powerful Progress D-27 propfan engine is a contra-rotating propfan with eight front blades and six back blades, but the D-27 has advanced composite blades with a reduced thickness-to-chord ratio and a more pronounced curvature at the leading edge.
[src:propfan/propfan] An engine that was launched in 1985, the D-27 delivers 14,000 hp (10,440 kW) of power with 27,000 lbf (119 kN) of thrust at takeoff.
[src:propfan/propfan] Two rear-mounted D-27 propfans propelled the Ukrainian Antonov An-180, which was scheduled for a 1995 first flight and a 1997 entry into service.
[src:propfan/propfan] In January 1994, Antonov rolled out the first prototype of the An-70 military transport aircraft, powered by four Progress D-27s attached to wings mounted to the top of the fuselage.
[src:propfan/propfan] The Russian Air Force placed an order for 164 aircraft in 2003, later canceled.
[src:propfan/propfan] As of 2013, the An-70 was still thought to have a promising future as a freighter.
[src:propfan/propfan] Since the propeller component of the Progress D-27 is made by Russia's SPE Aerosila, however, the An-70 was stymied by the Russo-Ukrainian War.
[src:propfan/propfan] Antonov began working instead with Turkey in 2018 to redevelop the An-70 as a rebranded An-77, so that the aircraft can comply with modern-day requirements without Russian supplier participation.
[src:propfan/propfan] In the first decade of the 21st century, rising jet fuel prices increased emphasis on engine/airframe efficiency to reduce emissions, which renewed interest in the propfan concept for jetliners beyond the Boeing 787 and Airbus A350XWB.
[src:propfan/propfan] For instance, Airbus patented aircraft designs with twin rear-mounted contra-rotating propfans.
[src:propfan/propfan] Rolls-Royce had the rear (pusher) configured RB.509-11 and front (tractor) configured RB.509-14 geared propfan designs, which produced 15,000–25,000 lbf thrust (6,800–11,300 kgf; 67–111 kN) using the gas generator from its XG-40 engine with 13,000 hp (9,700 kW) of shaft power.
[src:propfan/propfan] It became lukewarm on propfan technology in the 1980salthough it developed an open rotor design that was thought to be a finalist for the Irkut MS-21 narrowbody aircraft.
[src:propfan/propfan] The Rolls-Royce RB3011 engine would have a diameter of about 170 in (430 cm; 14 ft; 4.3 m) and require a 16,000 shaft hp (12,000 kW) gearbox.
[src:propfan/propfan] The European Commission launched an Open Rotor demonstration in 2008 led by Safran within the Clean Sky program funded with €65 million over eight years.
[src:propfan/propfan] A demonstrator was assembled in 2015, and ground tested in May 2017 on its open-air test rig in Istres, aiming to reduce fuel consumption and associated CO2 emissions by 30% compared with current CFM56 turbofans.
[src:propfan/propfan] After the completion of ground testing at the end of 2017, Safran's geared open rotor engine had reached technology readiness level 5.
[src:propfan/propfan] The demonstrator's twelve-blade front propeller and ten-blade back propeller had diameters of 13.1 and 12.5 ft (4.0 and 3.8 m; 160 and 150 in; 400 and 380 cm), respectively.
[src:propfan/propfan] The demonstrator, based on the core of the Snecma M88 military fighter engine, uses up to 12,200 horsepower (9 megawatts), provides a thrust of about 22,000 lbf (100 kN), and would cruise at a speed of Mach 0.75.
[src:propfan/propfan] Safran's future open rotor engine, however, would have a maximum diameter of almost 14.8 ft (4.50 m; 177 in; 450 cm).
[src:propfan/propfan] In 2007, the Progress D-27 was successfully modified to meet the United States Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) Stage 4 regulations, which correspond to International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) Chapter 4 standards.
[src:propfan/propfan] A 2012 trade study projected that propfan noise would be 10–13 decibels quieter than allowed by Stage 4 regulations.
[src:propfan/propfan] Stage 5 noise limits reduce the limits by only seven effective perceived noise decibels (EPNdB), within the propfan noise envelope.
[src:propfan/propfan] The study also projected that open rotors would be nine percent more fuel-efficient but remain 10–12 decibels louder than turbofans.
[src:propfan/propfan] Snecma claimed that its propfan engines would have about the same noise levels as its CFM LEAP turbofan engine.
[src:propfan/propfan] In 2021, CFM International announced its Revolutionary Innovation for Sustainable Engines (RISE) development program to produce a single-stage, gear-driven propfan paired with active stators in a puller/tractor, configuration with flight tests to begin by 2025.
[src:propfan/propfan] The rotor was expected to be 12–13 ft (3.7–4.0 m) in diameter.
[src:propfan/propfan] The company claimed its motivation was the global emphasis on reducing emissions.
[src:propfan/propfan] The engine was planned to support both hydrogen and sustainable aviation fuels.
[src:propfan/propfan] The engine was expected to include a compact high-pressure core and a recuperating system to preheat combustion air with exhaust heat along with ceramic matrix composites in the hot section and resin-transfer-molded composite fan blades.
[src:propfan/propfan] In addition to the rotor, the design includes a nonrotating set of variable-pitch stator blades that act as flow recovery vanes.
[src:propfan/propfan] The design increases the fan-pressure ratio and reduces rotor loading, increasing airspeed.
[src:propfan/propfan] The fan stage is to be powered by a high-speed booster compressor and a high-speed, low-pressure-shaft-driven front gearbox.
[src:propfan/propfan] The engine is slated for certification as an "integrated engine" instead of a traditional "propeller/engine" because of its airframe integration complexity.
[src:propfan/propfan] CFM planned for an aerodynamically three-dimensional rotor with 12 woven carbon-fiber composite blades.
[src:propfan/propfan] Aided by a smaller engine core, the CFM RISE engine would have a bypass ratio of 75.
[src:propfan/propfan] Turboprops have an optimum speed below about 450 mph (390 kn; 720 km/h), because propellers lose efficiency at high speed, due to an effect known as wave drag that occurs just below supersonic speeds.
[src:propfan/propfan] This powerful drag has a sudden onset, and it led to the concept of a sound barrier when first encountered in the 1940s.
[src:propfan/propfan] This effect can happen whenever the propeller is spun fast enough that the blade tips approach the speed of sound.
[src:propfan/propfan] The most effective way to address this problem is by adding blades to the propeller, allowing it to deliver more power at a lower rotational speed.
[src:propfan/propfan] This is why many World War II fighter designs started with two or three-blade propellers but by the end of the war were using up to five blades; as engines with more power were introduced, new propellers were needed to more efficiently convert that power.
[src:propfan/propfan] Adding blades makes the propeller harder to balance and maintain, and the additional blades cause minor performance penalties due to drag and efficiency issues.
[src:propfan/propfan] But even with these sorts of measures, eventually the forward speed of the plane combined with the rotational speed of the propeller blade tips (together known as the helical tip speed) will again result in wave drag problems.
[src:propfan/propfan] For most aircraft, this will occur at speeds over about 450 mph (390 kn; 720 km/h).
[src:propfan/propfan] A method of decreasing wave drag was discovered by German researchers in 1935—sweeping the wing backwards.
[src:propfan/propfan] Today, almost all aircraft designed to fly much above 450 mph (390 kn; 720 km/h) use a swept wing.
[src:propfan/propfan] This speed would be kept constant despite bigger or smaller propeller diameter by changing the maximum RPM.
[src:propfan/propfan] Drag can also be reduced by making the blades thinner, which increases the speed that the blades can attain before the air ahead of them becomes compressible and causes shock waves.
[src:propfan/propfan] For example, the blades of the Hamilton Standard test propfan had a thickness-to-chord ratio that tapered from less than 20% at the spinner junction to 2% at the tips, and 4% at mid-span.
[src:propfan/propfan] Propfan blades had approximately half the thickness-to-chord ratio of the best conventional propeller blades of the era, thinned to razor-like sharpness at their edges, and weighed as little as 20 pounds (9.1 kg).
[src:propfan/propfan] One of the major problems with the propfan is noise.
[src:propfan/propfan] The propfan research in the 1980s discovered ways to reduce noise, but at the cost of reduced fuel efficiency, mitigating some of the advantages of a propfan.
[src:propfan/propfan] General methods for reducing noise include lowering tip speeds and decreasing blade loading, or the amount of thrust per unit of blade surface area.
[src:propfan/propfan] A concept similar to wing loading, blade loading can be reduced by lowering the thrust requirement or by increasing the amount, width, and/or length of the blades.
[src:propfan/propfan] Engine makers expect propfan implementations to meet community (as opposed to cabin) noise regulations without sacrificing the efficiency advantage.
[src:propfan/propfan] Some think that propfans can potentially cause less of a community impact than turbofans, given their lower rotational speeds.
[src:propfan/propfan] Geared propfans should have an advantage over ungeared propfans for the same reason.
[src:propfan/propfan] In 2007, the Progress D-27 was modified to meet the United States Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) Stage 4 regulations, which correspond to International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) Chapter 4 standards and were adopted in 2006.
[src:propfan/propfan] A 2012 trade study by NASA projected that noise from existing open rotor technology would be 10–13 cumulative EPNdB quieter than the maximum noise level allowed by the Stage 4 regulations.
[src:propfan/propfan] Snecma estimates from open-rotor tests that its propfan engines would have about the same noise levels as its CFM LEAP turbofan engine, which entered service in 2016.
[src:propfan/propfan] Further reductions can be achieved by redesigning the aircraft structure to shield noise from the ground.
[src:propfan/propfan] For example, another study estimated that if propfan engines were used to power a hybrid wing body aircraft instead of a conventional tube-and-wing aircraft, noise levels could be reduced by as much as 38 cumulative EPNdB compared to ICAO Chapter 4 requirements.
[src:propfan/propfan] In 2007, the British budget airline easyJet introduced its ecoJet concept, a 150–250 seat aircraft with V-mounted open rotor engines joined to the rear fuselage and shielded by a U-tail.
[src:propfan/propfan] It unsuccessfully initiated discussions with Airbus, Boeing, and Rolls-Royce to produce the aircraft.
[src:propfan/propfan] A twin-engine aircraft carrying 100–150 passengers would require propfan diameters of 120–168 inches (300–430 cm; 10.0–14.0 ft; 3.0–4.3 m), and a propfan with a propeller diameter of 236 in (600 cm; 19.7 ft; 6.0 m) would theoretically produce almost 60,000 lbf (270 kN) of thrust.
[src:propfan/propfan] These sizes achieve the desired high bypass ratios of over 30, but they are approximately twice the diameter of turbofan engines of equivalent capability.
[src:propfan/propfan] For this reason, airframers usually design the empennage with a T-tail configuration in order to avoid the turbulent propwash adversely influencing the elevators and causing vibration issues therein.
[src:propfan/propfan] The propfans may be attached to the upper part of the rear fuselage.
[src:propfan/propfan] For the Rolls-Royce RB3011 propfan prototype, a pylon of about 8.3 ft (2.54 m; 100 in; 254 cm) long would be required to connect the center of each engine to the side of the fuselage.
[src:propfan/propfan] If the propfans are mounted to the wings, the wings would be attached to the aircraft in a high wing configuration, which allows for ground clearance without requiring excessively long landing gear.
[src:propfan/propfan] For the same amount of power or thrust produced, an unducted fan requires shorter blades than a geared propfan, although the overall installation issues still apply.
[src:propfan/propfan] Turboprops and most propfans are rated by the amount of shaft horsepower (shp) that they produce, as opposed to turbofans and the UDF propfan type, which are rated by the amount of thrust they put out.
[src:propfan/propfan] The rule of thumb is that at sea level with a static engine, 1 shaft horsepower (750 watts) is roughly equivalent of 2 pounds-force (8.9 N) thrust, but at cruise altitude, that changes to about 1 pound-force (4.4 N) thrust.
[src:propfan/propfan] That means two 25,000 lbf thrust (110 kN) engines can theoretically be replaced with a pair of 12,000–13,000 shaft hp (8,900–9,700 kW) propfans or with two 25,000 lbf thrust (110 kN) UDF propfans.
